1164: 
1165: Race looked at the cover page again, scanned the rough texture of the photocopier's ink. Then he took a deep breath and turned the page. 
1166: 
1167: He saw the first line, written in fine medieval calligraphy: 
1168: 
1169: MELIS NOMINI EST ALBERTO LIIIS SANTIAGO ET ILLG EST MELIN[ 
1170: 
1171: He translated. 
1172: 
1173: My name is Alberto Luis Santiago and this is my stoW… 
1174: 
1175: FIRST READING 
1176: 
1177: 
1178: 
1179: On the first day of the ninth month in the year of Our Lord 1535, I became a traitor to my country. 
1180: 
1181: The reason: I helped a man escape from a prison of my countrymen. 
1182: 
1183: His name was Renco Capac and he claimed to be an Incan prince, the younger brother of their supreme ruler, Manco Capac, the man they called the Sapa Inca. 
1184: 
1185: He was a handsome man, with smooth olive skin and long black hair. His most distinctive feature, however, was a prominent birthmark situated directly below his left eye. It looked like an inverted mountain peak, a ragged triangle of brown skin that sat atop his otherwise clear complexion. 
1186: 
1187: I first met Renco on board the San Vicente, a prison hulk that lay out in the middle of the Urubamba River, ten miles north of the Incans' apital, Cuzco. 
1188: 
1189: The San Vicente was the foulest of all the prison hulks that lay at anchor in the rivers of New Spain—an old wooden galleon no longer fit for ocean travel that had been dismasted and hauled overland for the sole purpose of housing hostile or dangerous Indians. 
1190: 
1191: Armed as usual with my prized leather-bound Bible a three-hundred-page handwritten version of the great book that had been a gift to me from my parents upon my enter ing the Holy Orders—I had come to the prison hulk to teach these heathens the Word of Our Lord. 
1192: 
1193: It was in this capacity as a minister of our Faith that I met the young prince Renco. Unlike most of the others in that 
1194: 
1195: 
1196: 
1197: miserable hulk—foul, ugly wretches who, owing to the shameful conditions my countrymen imposed on them, looked more as dogs than men—he was well spoken and educated. He was also possessed of a most unique sensitiv ity the likes of which I have not seen in any man since. It was a gentleness, an understanding, a look in his eyes that penetrated my very soul. 
1198: 
1199: He was also of considerable intelligence. My countrymen had been in New Spain for but three years and he could already speak our language. He was also eager to learn of my Faith and understand my people and our ways, and I was happy to teach him. In any case, we soon struck up a friendship and I visited him often. 
1200: 
1201: And then one day he told me of his mission. 
1202: 
1203: Before he had been captured, so he said, this prince had been charged with travelling to Cuzco and retrieving an idol of some sort. Not an ordinary idol, mind, but a most venerated idol, perhaps the most venerated idol of these Indians. An idol which they say embodies their spirit. 
1204: 
1205: But Renco had been waylaid on his journey to Cuzco, captured in an ambush set up by the Governor with the aid of the Chancas, an extremely hostile tribe from the northern jungles that had been subjugated by the Incan people against their will. 
1206: 
1207: Like many other tribes from this region, the Chancas saw :he arrival of my countrymen as a means of breaking the yoke of Incan tyranny. They were quick to offer their ser vices to the Governor as informers and as guides, in return for which they received muskets and metal swords, for the tribes of New Spain have no concept of bronze or iron. 
1208: 
1209: As Renco informed me of his mission and his capture at the hands of the Governor, I saw over his shoulder a Chanca tribesman who was also being held captive inside the San Vicente. 
1210: 
1211: His name was Castino and he was an ugly brute of a man. Tall and hairy, bearded and unwashed, he could not have been more dissimilar to the young articulate Renco. He was an utterly repulsive creature, the most frightening 
1212: 
1213: 
1214: 
1215: form I have ever had the misfortune to lay my eyes 
1216: 
1217: A sharpened piece of white bone pierced the skin of 
1218: 
1219: his left cheek, the characteristic mark of the Chancas. 
1220: 
1221: always stared malevolently at Renco's back when ever I came to visit the young prince. 
1222: 
1223: The day he told me of his mission to retrieve the idol, 
1224: 
1225: was extremely distressed. 
1226: 
1227: The object of his quest, he said, was locked inside a vault 
1228: 
1229: .inside the Coricancha, or sun temple, at Cuzco. But Renco 
1230: 
1231: that day learned—by eavesdropping on a conversation 
1232: 
1233: two guards on board the hulk—that the city of 
1234: 
1235: Cuzco had recently fallen and that the Spaniards were 
1236: 
1237: inside its walls, sacking and looting it unopposed. 
1238: 
1239: I, too, had heard of the taking of Cuzco. It was said that 
1240: 
1241: the looting taking place there was some of the most rapa cious of the entire conquest. Rumours abounded of 
1242: 
1243: Spaniards killing their fellow soldiers in their lust for the 
1244: 
1245: mountains of gold that lay inside the city's walls. 
1246: 
1247: Such tales filled me with dismay. I had arrived in New 
1248: 
1249: Spain but six months previously with all the foolish ideals 
1250: 
1251: of a novice—desires of converting all the pagan natives to 
1252: 
1253: our noble Catholic Faith, dreams of leading a column of soldiers while holding forth a crucifix, delusions of building 
1254: 
1255: high-spired churches that would be the envy of Europe. But 
1256: 
1257: these ideals were quickly dispelled by the wanton acts of 
1258: 
1259: cruelty and greed that I witnessed of my countrymen every 
1260: 
1261: day. 
1262: 
1263: Murder, pillage, rapethese were not the acts of men 
1264: 
1265: fighting in the name of God. They were the acts of 
1266: 
1267: scoundrels, of villains. And indeed at the moments when 
1268: 
1269: my disillusionment was at its greatest—such as the time 
1270: 
1271: when I witnessed a Spanish soldier decapitate a woman in 
1272: 
1273: order to seize her gold necklace—I would wonder whether 
1274: 
1275: I was fighting for the right side. That Spanish soldiers had 
1276: 
1277: taken to killing each other during their plunder of Cuzco 
1278: 
1279: came as no surprise to me. 
1280: 
1281: I should also add at this juncture, however, that I had 
1282: 
1283: heard rumours about Renco's sacred idol before. 
1284: 
1285: 
1286: 
1287: It was widely known that Hernando Pizarro, the Gover nor's brother and chief lieutenant, had put up an incredible bounty for any information that led to the discovery of the idol's whereabouts. It was to my mind a tribute to the rev erence and devotion that the Incans paid their idol that not one of them—not a single one of them—had betrayed its location in return for Hernando's fabulous reward. It shames me to say that I do not believe my countrymen, in similar circumstances, would have done the same. 
1288: 
1289: But of all the tales I had heard of the looting of Cuzco, nowhere had I heard of the discovery of the treasured Incan idol. 
1290: 
1291: Indeed, if it had been found, word would have spread faster than the wind. For the lucky foot soldier who dis covered it would have been instantly knighted, would have been made a marquis by the Governor on the spot and would have lived the rest of his life back in Spain in unreserved luxury. 
1292: 
1293: And yet there had been no such tale. 
1294: 
1295: Which led me to conclude that the Spaniards in Cuzco had not yet found the idol. 
1296: 
1297: 'Brother Alberto,' Renco said, his eyes pleading, 'help me. Help me escape this floating cage so that I can complete my mission. Only I can retrieve the idol of my people. And 
1298: 
1299: with the Spaniards holding Cuzco, it is only a matter of time 
1300: 
1301: • before they find it.' 
1302: 
1303: Well. 
1304: 
1305: I did not know what to say. I could never do such a thing. 
1306: 
1307: I could never help him escape. I would be making myself a hunted man, a traitor to my country. If I were caught, I would be the one imprisoned inside this hellish floating dungeon. And so I left the hulk without another word. 
1308: 
1309: But I would return. And I would talk with Renco again—and again he would ask me to help him, his voice impassioned, his eyes begging. 
1310: 
1311: And whenever I contemplated the issue more closely, my mind would always return to two things: my total and utter disillusionment at the despicable acts of those men I called 
1312: 
1313: 
1314: 
1315: my countrymen, and—conversely—my admiration of the Incan people's stoic refusal to disclose the secret location of their idol in the face of such overwhelming adversity. 
1316: 
1317: Indeed, never had I witnessed such unfailing devotion. I envied their faith. I had heard tell of Hernando torturing entire villages in his obsessive search for the idol, had heard of the atrocities he had committed. I wondered how I would act if I were to see my own kinfolk butchered, tortured, mur dered. In those circumstances, would I disclose the location of Jerusalem? 
1318: 
1319: In the end, I decided that I would and I was doubly ashamed. 
1320: 
1321: And so despite myself, my Faith and my allegiance to my country, I decided to help Renco. 
1322: 
1323: 
1324: 
1325: I left the hulk and returned later that night, bringing with me a young page—an Incan named Tupac—just as Renco had instructed me. We both wore hooded cloaks against the cold and kept our hands folded inside our sleeves. 
1326: 
1327: We came to the guard station on the riverbank. As it happened, since most of my country's forces were at Cuzco partaking in the looting there, only a small group of soldiers were on hand in the tent village near the hulk. Indeed, only a lone night guard—a fat slovenly thug from Madrid with liquor on his breath and dirt under his fingernails—guarded the bridge that led to the hulk. 
1328: 
1329: After taking a second glance at young Tupac—it was not uncommon at that time for young Indians to serve as pages for monks like myself—the night guard belched loudly and ordered us to inscribe our names on the register. 
1330: 
1331: I scratched both of our names in the book. Then when I had finished, the two of us stepped onto the narrow wooden footbridge that stretched out from the riverbank over to a door set into the side of the prison hulk in the middle of the river. 
1332: 
1333: No sooner had we stepped past the filthy night guard, however, than the young Tupac whirled around quickly 
1334: 
1335: 
1336: 
1337: and grabbed the man from behind and twisted his head, breaking his neck in an instant. The guard's body slumped in its chair. I winced at the sheer violence of the act, but strangely I found that I felt little sympathy for the guard. I had made my decision—had pledged my allegiance to the enemy—and there was no turning back 
1338: 
1339: now. 
1340: 
1341: My young companion quickly took the guard's rifle and his pistallo-or 'pistol' as some of my countrymen were now calling them—and, last of all, his keys. Tupac then affixed a stone weight to the dead guard's foot and dropped the body into the river. 
1342: 
1343: In the pale blue moonlight, we crossed the rickety wooden footbridge and entered the hulk. 
1344: 
1345: The interior guard leapt to his feet as we entered the cage room but Tupac was far too quick for him. He fired his pistol at the guard without missing a step. The explosion of the gunshot in the enclosed space of the prison hulk was deafening. Prisoners all around us awoke with a start at the sudden terrifying sound. 
1346: 
1347: Renco was already on his feet as we came to his cage. 
1348: 
1349: The guard's key fitted perfectly in the lock of his cell and the door opened easily. The prisoners all around us were shouting and banging on the bars of their cages, pleading to be released. My eyes darted around in every direction and in the midst of all this uproar, I saw a sight that chilled me to my very core. 
1350: 
1351: I saw the Chanca, Castino, standing in his cell—standing perfectly still—staring at me intently. 
1352: 
1353: His cage now open, Renco ran over to the dead guard's corpse, grabbed his weapons and handed them to me. 
1354: 
1355: 'Come on,' he said, awakening me from Castino's hyp notic stare. Dressed only in the barest of prison rags, Renco quickly began to undress the dead guard's corpse. Then he hurriedly put on the guard's thick leather riding jacket, pantaloons and boots. 
1356: 
1357: No sooner was he dressed than he was on his feet again, unlocking some of the other cages. I noticed that he only 
1358: 
1359: 
1360: 
1361: the cages of Incan warriors and not those of pris- from subjugated tribes like the Chancas. 
1362: 
1363: And then suddenly Renco was dashing out the door with rifle in his hand, ignoring the shouts of the other prison- 
1364: 
1365: and calling for me to follow. 
1366: 
1367: We dashed back across the rickety footbridge, amid a 
1368: 
1369: of running prisoners. By this time, however, others heard the commotion on board the hulk. Four 
1370: 
1371: from the nearby tent village arrived at the river- 
1372: 
1373: on horseback just as we leapt off the bridge. They fired :us with their muskets, the reports of their weapons boom- 
1374: 
1375: like thunderclaps in the night. 
1376: 
1377: Renco fired back, handling his musket like the most sea- 
1378: 
1379: Spanish infantryman, blasting one of the horsemen 
1380: 
1381: his mount. The other Incan prisoners ran ahead of us and overpowered two of the other horsemen. 
1382: 
1383: The last horseman brought his steed around so that it stood directly in front of me. In a flashing instant, I saw him register my appearance—a European helping these heathens. 
1384: 
1385: I saw the anger flare in his eyes and then I saw him raise his rifle in my direction. 
1386: 
1387: With nothing else to call on, I hastily raised my own pistol and fired it. The pistol boomed loudly in my hand and I would swear on the Good Book itself that its recoil almost tore my arm from its. socket. The horseman in front of me snapped backwards in his saddle and tumbled to the ground, dead. 
1388: 
1389: I stood there, stunned, holding the pistol in my hand, staring fixedly at the dead body on the ground. I endeavoured to convince myself that I had done no wrong. He had been going to kill me 
1390: 
1391: 'Brother!' Renco called suddenly. 
1392: 
1393: I turned on the moment and saw him sitting astride one of the Spanish horses. 'Come!' he called. 'Take his horse! We have to get to Cuzco!' 
1394: 
1395: 
1396: 
1397: The city of Cuzco lies at the head of a long mountain valley that runs in a north-south direction. It is a walled city that is situated between two parallel rivers, the Huatanay and the Tullumayo, which act rather like moats. 
1398: 
1399: Situated on a hill to the north of the city, towering above it, is the most dominant feature of the Cuzco valley. There, looking down over the city like a god, is the stone fortress of Sacsayhuaman. 
1400: 
1401: Sacsayhuaman is a structure like no other I have seen in all of the world. Nothing in Spain, or even in the whole of Europe, can compare with its size and sheer dominating presence. 
1402: 
1403: Truly, it is a most fearsome citadel—roughly pyramidal in shape, it consists of three colossal tiers, each one easily a hundred hands high, with walls constructed of gigantic hundred-ton blocks. 
1404: 
1405: These Incans do not have mortar, but they more than make up for that deficiency with their extraordinary abilities in the art of stonemasonry. Rather than bind stones together with pastes, they build all of their fortresses, temples and palaces by fashioning enormous boulders into regular shapes and placing them alongside each other so that each boulder fits perfectly with the next. So exact are the joins between these monumental stones, so perfectly are they cut, that one cannot slip a knife blade between them. 
1406: 
1407: It was in this setting that the intriguing siege of Cuzco took place. 
1408: 
1409: 
1410: 
1411: Now, it is at this point that it should be said that the siege of Cuzco must rank as one of the strangest in the history of 
1412: 
1413: nodern warfare. 
1414: 
1415: The strangeness of the siege stems from the following fact: during it the invaders—my countrymen, the Spaniards— were inside the city walls, while the owners of the city, the 
1416: 
1417: Incan people, were positioned outside the city walls. 
1418: 
1419: In other words, the Incans were laying siege to their own 
1420: 
1421: To be fair, this situation came about as the result of a long 
1422: 
1423: complicated chain of events. In 1533, my Spanish countrymen rode into Cuzco unopposed and, at first, they were 
1424: 
1425: to the Incans. It was only when they began to per- 
1426: 
1427: the full extent of the riches within the city walls that any pretence of civility vanished. 
1428: 
1429: My countrymen pillaged Cuzco with a frenzy never before 
1430: 
1431: Native men were brutally enslaved. Native women ,,vere ravaged. Gold was melted down by the wagonload—after 
1432: 
1433: which time the Incans began calling my Spanish countrymen 'gold-eaters'. Apparently, they thought that my countrymen's insatiable lust for gold stemmed from our need to eat it. 
1434: 
1435: By 1535, the Sapa Inca—Renco's brother, Manco Capac— 
1436: 
1437: until that time been conciliatory in nature toward my 
1438: 
1439: . fled the capital for the mountains and assembled an enormous army with .which he planned to retake Cuzco. 
1440: 
1441: The Incan army—100 000 strong, but armed only with sticks and clubs and arrows—descended upon the city of Cuzco in a fury and they took Sacsayhuaman, the massive stone citadel overlooking the city, in a day. The Spaniards 
1442: 
1443: took refuge inside the city walls. 
1444: 
1445: And so the siege began. 
1446: 
1447: It would last for three months. 
1448: 
1449: 
1450: 
1451: Nothing on this earth could have prepared me for the sight that I beheld when I rode through the enormous stone tollgates at the northern end of the Cuzco valley. 
1452: 
1453: It was night, but it might as well have been day. Fires 
1454: 
1455: 
1456: 
1457: burned everywhere, both within the city walls and without. 
1458: 
1459: It looked like Hell itself. 
1460: 
1461: The largest force of men I have ever seen filled the valley before me, an undulating mass of humanity pouring down from the citadel on the hill toward the city—100 000 Incans, all of them on foot, shouting and screaming and waving torches and weapons. They had the entire city surrounded. 
1462: 
1463: Inside the city walls, fires could be seen ravaging the stone buildings situated there. 
1464: 
1465: Renco rode ahead of me, right into the seething mass of people, and like the Red Sea for Moses, the crowd parted for him. 
1466: 
1467: And as it did so, an enormous roar went up from the Incans, a cheer of rejoice, a shout of such fervour and cele bration that it made the hairs on my neck stand on end. 
1468: 
1469: It was as if they had all recognised Renco instantly— despite the fact that he was dressed in Spanish clothing—and stood aside for him. It was as if every single one of them knew of his mission and would do their utmost to allow him every possible haste in effecting it. 
1470: 
1471: Renco and I charged through the teeming mass of people, galloping at tremendous speed as the hordes of cheering Incans opened up before us and urged us on. 
1472: 
1473: We dismounted near the base of the mighty fortress Sac- sayhuaman and walked quickly through a crowd of Indian warriors. 
1474: 
1475: As we walked through the Incan ranks, I saw that numer ous stakes had been driven into the ground all around us. 
1476: 
1477: Mounted on top of the stakes were the bloodied heads of Spanish soldiers. On some stakes, the entire bodies of cap tured Spaniards had been impaled. Their heads and feet had been hacked off. I walked quickly, mindful to stay close behind my friend Renco. 
1478: 
1479: Then all at once, the crowd in front of us parted and I saw, standing before me at one of the entrances to the giant stone fortress, an Indian dressed in a most glorious manner. 
1480: 
1481: He wore a dazzling red cape and a gold-plated necklace and on his head sat a magnificent jewel-encrusted crown. He 
1482: 
1483: 
1484: 
1485: was surrounded by an entourage of at least twenty warriors and attendants. 
1486: 
1487: It was Manco. The Sapa Inca. 
1488: 
1489: Manco embraced Renco and they exchanged words in Quechuan, the Incans' language. Renco later translated it for me thus: 
1490: 
1491: 'Brother,' said the Sapa Inca. 'We were anxious as to your whereabouts. We heard that you had been captured, or worse, killed. And you are the only one who is permitted to enter the vault and rescue the—' 
1492: 
1493: 'Yes, brother, I know,' said Renco. 'Listen, we have no time. I must enter the city now. Has the river entrance been used yet?' 
1494: 
1495: 'No,' said Manco, 'we have refrained from using it as you instructed, so as not to alert the gold-eaters of its existence.' 
1496: 
1497: 'Good,' said Renco. He hesitated before he spoke again. 'I 
1498: 
1499: have another question.' 
1500: 
1501: 'What is it?' 
1502: 
1503: 'Bassario,' said Renco. 'Is he inside the city walls?' 
1504: 
1505: 'Bassario?' Manco frowned. 'Well, I… I do not know…' 
1506: 
1507: 'Was he in the city when it fell?' 
1508: 
1509: 'Well, yes.' 
1510: 
1511: 'Where was he?' 
1512: 
1513: 'Why, he was in the peasant prison,' said Manco. 'Where he has been for the past Year. Where he belongs. Why? What need have you of a fiend like Bassario?' 
1514: 
1515: 'Let it not concern you now, brother,' said Renco. 'For it will matter for nothing if I do not find the idol first.' 
1516: 
1517: Just then there came an almighty commotion from some where behind us and both Renco and I turned. 
1518: 
1519: What I saw filled my heart with unimaginable horror: a column of Spanish soldiers—no fewer than three hundred of them, resplendent in their forged silver armour and distinc tive pointed helmets—came charging into the valley from the northern tollgates, their muskets firing. Their horses were covered in heavy silver plating and, thus protected, the mounted Spanish troops cut a swathe through the ranks of the Incan warriors in front of them. 
1520: 
1521: 
1522: 
1523: As I watched the column of conquistadors hack their way through the Incan ranks, trampling the Indians before them, I beheld two of the riders near the head of the procession, both of whom I recognised. The first was the Captain, Her- nando Pizarro, the Governor's brother and a most cruel man. His distinctive black moustache and unkempt woolly beard were visible even from where I stood, four hundred paces away. 
1524: 
1525: The second horseman was a figure whom I recognised with some degree of dread. Indeed, so much so that I took a 
1526: 
1527: second glance at him. But my worst fears were confirmed. 
1528: 
1529: It was Castino. 
1530: 
1531: The brutish Chanca who had been in the San Vicente with Renco. Only now he rode with his hands unmanacled— free—alongside Hernando. 
1532: 
1533: And then all at once I understood. 
1534: 
1535: Castino must have overheard my conversations with Renco… 
1536: 
1537: He was leading Hernando to the vault inside the Coricancha. 
1538: 
1539: Renco knew this, too. 'By the gods,' said he. He turned 
1540: 
1541: with haste to his brother. 'I must go. I must go now.” 
1542: 
1543: 'Speed to you, brother,' said Manco. 
1544: 
1545: Renco nodded curtly to the Sapa Inca and then turned to me and said in Spanish, 'Come. We must hurry.' 
1546: 
1547: We left the Sapa Inca and hastened around to the south side of the city, the side furthest from Sacsayhuaman. As we did so, I saw Hernando and his horsemen charge in through the city's northern gate. 
1548: 
1549: 'Where are we going?' I inquired as we strode quickly through the angry crowd. 
1550: 
1551: 'To the lower river,' was all my companion said in reply. 
1552: 
1553: At length, we came to the river which ran alongside the southern wall of the city. I looked up at the wall on the other side of the stream and saw Spanish soldiers armed with muskets and swords walking the ramparts, silhouetted by the orange light of the fires burning behind them. 
1554: 
1555: Renco strode purposefully toward the river and, to my 
1556: 
1557: 
1558: 
1559: great surprise, stepped boots-and-all straight into the water. 
1560: 
1561: 'Wait!' I cried. 'Where are you going?' 
1562: 
1563: 'Down there,' said he, indicating the body of water. 
1564: 
1565: 'But I… I can't. I can't go in there with you.' 
1566: 
1567: Renco gripped my arm firmly. 'My friend Alberto, I thank you from the bottom of my heart for what you have done, what you have risked to allow me to complete my mission. 
1568: 
1569: But now I must hurry if I am to succeed in my quest. Join me, Alberto. Stay with me. Complete my mission with me. Look at these people. While you are with me, you are a hero to them. But while you are not, you are just another gold-eater who must be killed. And now I must go. I cannot stay behind with you. If you stay here, I will not be able to help you. 
1570: 
1571: Come with me, Alberto. Dare to live.' 
1572: 
1573: I looked at the Incan warriors behind me. Even with their primitive sticks and clubs, they still looked fierce and dan gerous. I saw a Spanish soldier's head on a stake nearby, its mouth open in a grotesque yawn. 
1574: 
1575: 'I think I will go with you,' said I, turning and stepping waist-deep into the water next to him. 
1576: 
1577: 'All right, then. Take a deep breath,' said he, 'and follow 
1578: 
1579: me.' 
1580: 
1581: And with that Renco held his breath and disappeared under the water. I shook my head and, despite myself, took a deep breath and followed him under the surface. 
1582: 
1583: 
1584: 
1585: Silence. 
1586: 
1587: The chants and shouts of the Incan hordes were gone 
1588: 
1589: now. 
1590: 
1591: In the darkness of the murky river I followed Renco's kicking feet into a circular stone pipe that was set into the underwater wall of the city. 
1592: 
1593: It was difficult to pull myself through the submerged cylindrical tunnel, its confines were so narrow. And it seemed to go on for an eternity. But then, just when it seemed as if my lungs would burst, I saw the end of the pipe and the rippling waves of the surface beyond it and I pulled myself harder through the water toward them. 
1594: 
1595: I arose inside an underground sewer of some kind, lit by • flaming torches mounted on the walls. I was standing waist-deep in water. Damp stone walls surrounded me. 
1596: 
1597: Square-shaped stone tunnels stretched away into the dark ness. The foul stench of human faeces filled the air. 
1598: 
1599: Renco was already wading through the water away from me, toward a junction in the tunnel system. I hurried after him. 
1600: 
1601: Through the tunnels we went. Left then right, left then right—thus we made our way hastily through the under ground labyrinth. Never once did Renco seem lost or doubtful—he just turned into each tunnel with confidence and purpose. 
1602: 
1603: And then all at once he stopped and stared up at the stone ceiling above us. 
1604: 
1605: 
1606: 
1607: I just stood behind him, perplexed. I could see no differ ence between this tunnel and any of the other half-dozen that we had just come through. 
1608: 
1609: And then for some reason unknown to myself, Renco ducked underneath the foul-smelling water. Moments later, he came up with a rock the size of a man's fist. Then he climbed up out of the water and stood astride the narrow ledge that lined the tunnel and with his newfound rock began to hit the underside of one of the stone slabs that 
1610: 
1611: formed the ceiling of the tunnel. 
1612: 
1613: Bang-bang. Bang. 
1614: 
1615: Renco waited for a moment. Then he repeated the same sequence. 
1616: 
1617: Bang-bang. Bang. 
1618: 
1619: It was a code of some sort. Renco stepped back down into the water and we both stared up at the wet stone ceiling in 
1620: 
1621: silence, waiting for something to happen. 
1622: 
1623: Nothing happened. 
1624: 
1625: We kept waiting. As we did so, I noticed a small symbol carved into the corner of the stone slab that Renco had been assailing. It was a carving of a circle, with a double 'V' 
1626: 
1627: inscribed within it. 
1628: 
1629: And then all of a sudden—boom-boom, boom—a series of muffled whumps could be heard from the other side of the ceiling. Someone repeating Renco's code. 
1630: 
1631: Renco sighed with relief. Then he stood up on the ledge again and pounded out a new sequence of thumps. 
1632: 
1633: Moments later, the whole square-shaped section of the ceiling slid away, grinding loudly against its neighbours, revealing a dark, cavern-like space above us. 
1634: 
1635: Renco immediately climbed up out of the water and disappeared into the hole in the ceiling. I followed. 
1636: 
1637: I came up inside a most splendid room, an enormous vault- like chamber, lined on all four sides with magnificent golden images. All four walls of the chamber were made of solid stone blocks, each one ten feet wide and probably as thick. 
1638: 
1639: There was no obvious door, except for a smaller stone this one only six feet in height—set within one of the sturdy walls. 
1640: 
1641: 
1642: 
1643: I was in the vault of the Coricancha. 
1644: 
1645: A single flaming torch illuminated the cavernous space. 
1646: 
1647: It was held by a burly Incan warrior. Three other equally large warriors stood behind the torchbearer, glaring at me. 
1648: 
1649: There was another person in the vault, however. An elderly woman, and she had eyes only for Renco. 
1650: 
1651: She was a handsome woman, with grey hair and wrinkled skin, and I imagined that in her prime she must have been a strikingly beautiful woman. She was dressed simply, in a white cotton robe and a gold-and-emerald headdress. 
1652: 
1653: And I must say that in her simple white attire, she looked 
1654: 
1655: angelic, almost heavenly, like a priestess of some 
1656: 
1657: Boom[ 
1658: 
1659: I spun at the sudden noise. Renco did, too. 
1660: 
1661: Boom[ 
1662: 
1663: It seemed to come from the other side of the walls. Someone pounding on the outside of the stone door. 
1664: 
1665: I froze in horror. 
1666: 
1667: The Spaniards. 
1668: 
1669: Hernando. 
1670: 
1671: They were trying to get in. 
1672: 
1673: The old priestess said something to Renco in Quechuano Renco replied quickly and then he gestured toward me. 
1674: 
1675: Boom[ Boom[ 
1676: 
1677: The old priestess then turned hurriedly to a stone pedestal behind her. I saw on the pedestal an object covered with a purple silk-like cloth. 
1678: 
1679: The priestess picked up the object-cloth and all—and despite the insistent pounding on the walls, handed it solemnly to Renco. I still could not see what lay beneath the cloth. Whatever it was, it was about the size and shape of a human head. 
1680: 
1681: Renco took the object respectfully. 
1682: 
1683: Boom[ Boom! 
1684: 
1685: Why was he moving so slowly, I wondered incredulously, as my eyes darted to the shuddering stone walls around us. 
1686: 
1687: 
1688: 
1689: Once the object was safely in his hands, Renco slowly 
1690: 
1691: removed its cloth. 
1692: 
1693: And I saw it. 
1694: 
1695: And for a moment, I could do nothing but stare. 
1696: 
1697: It was the most beautiful, and yet at the same time the most fearsome-looking idol I had ever seen. 
1698: 
1699: It was completely black, carved out of a square block of a very unusual type of stone. It was rough and sharp at the edges, the workmanship crude, uneven. Out of the middle 
1700: 
1701: of the block had been carved the visage of a fierce mountain cat with its jaws bared wide. It looked as if the cat— deranged with rage and fury—had managed to push its 
1702: 
1703: head out of the very stone itself. 
1704: 
1705: Imperfections within the rock—thin rivulets of the most 
1706: 
1707: shade of purple—-ran vertically down the cat's face, making the image appear even more fearsome, if indeed such a thing were possible. 
1708: 
1709: Renco covered the idol once again. As he did so, the old priestess stepped forward and placed something around his neck. It was a thin leather cord with a dazzling green gem stone attached to it—a magnificent shining emerald that was easily the size of a man's ear. Renco accepted the gift 
1710: 
1711: with a solemn bow and then turned quickly to face me. 
1712: 
1713: 'We must go now,' said he. 
1714: 
1715: Then, with the idol under his arm, he made for the hole in the floor. I hurried after“ him. The four burly warriors all took hold of the great stone slab that would cover our exit. 
1716: 
1717: The old priestess did not move. 
1718: 
1719: Renco climbed down into the sewer. I lowered myself after him. As I did so, however, I noticed something quite peculiar. 
1720: 
1721: The vault was silent. 
1722: 
1723: The pounding outside had stopped. 
1724: 
1725: And as I pondered this curiosity some more, I realised with some dread that the pounding had in fact ceased some goodly time before. 
1726: 
1727: It was then that the entrance to the vault exploded inwards. 
1728: 
1729: 
1730: 
1731: A great flash of white flared out around the edges of the huge stone doorway, and an instant later, the whole six-foot doorstone just blasted out into a thousand fragments, show ering the vault room with fist-sized rocks. 
1732: 
1733: I couldn't explain it. A battering ram could not possibly have fragmented so large a stone so instantaneously… 
1734: 
1735: And then the smoke and dust in the doorway cleared and I saw the great black barrel of a cannon in the space where 
1736: 
1737: the doorstone had been. 
1738: 
1739: My mind reeled. 
1740: 
1741: They had blown open the vault door with a cannon! 
1742: 
1743: 'Come on!' Renco called from the sewer beneath me. 
1744: 
1745: I immediately started lowering myself into the hole, just as the first Spanish soldiers came charging in through the dustcloud, firing their muskets in every direction. 
1746: 
1747: And as I disappeared through the hole in the floor, the last thing I saw was the Captain, Hernando Pizarro, striding into the vault room with a pistol in his hand. His eyes were wild, and his head turned this way and that as he searched the vault for the idol that he so longed for. 
1748: 
1749: And then, in a single horrifying instant, I saw Hernando look down in my direction and stare directly into my eyes. 
1750: 
1751: 
1752: 
1753: I sloshed madly through the dark sewer tunnels, trying with all my might to keep up with Renco. As I did so, I heard shouts in Spanish echoing off the hard stone walls of the tunnels, saw long ominous shadows stretching out around the corners behind us. 
1754: 
1755: Ahead of me, Renco just plunged onward through the filthy water with the Incan idol under his arm. 
1756: 
1757: We hastened through the tunnels, waist-deep in the water, ducking left, bending right, weaving our way through the dark stone labyrinth back toward the river entrance and freedom. 
1758: 
1759: After a while, however, I began to notice that we were racing in the wrong direction. 
1760: 
1761: Renco was not heading back toward the river entrance. 
1762: 
1763: 'Where are we going!' I called forward. 
1764: 
1765: 'Just move!' he called back. 
1766: 
1767: I turned a corner just as a torch on the wall above my head was blasted from its mount by a musket shot. I turned and saw a team of six conquistadors wading through the tunnel behind me, the flaming torchlight of the passageway glinting off their helmets. 
1768: 
1769: 'They're right behind us!' I called. 
1770: 
1771: 'Then run faster!' 
1772: 
1773: More musket shots rang out, loud as thunderclaps, deafening my ears. Their projectiles exploded against the damp stone walls around us. 
1774: 
1775: Just then, ahead of me, I saw Renco leap up onto a ledge 
1776: 
1777: 
1778: 
1779: and push up with his shoulder against a stone slab in the ceiling—a slab which I saw bore in its corner the same mysterious symbol that I had seen before, the circle with the double 'V' 
1780: 
1781: inside it. I leapt up onto the ledge after him and helped him heave the stone upward, revealing the starry night sky. 
1782: 
1783: Renco climbed out first and I followed immediately behind him. We were standing in a narrow cobblestoned street of some sort. Impenetrable grey walls lined both sides of the alleyway. 
1784: 
1785: I hurriedly began to replace the stone slab when all of a sudden, a musket shot from within the tunnel pinged against the edge of the hole, narrowly missing my fingers. 
1786: 
1787: 'Never mind. Come on, this way,' said Renco, pulling me down the tiny street. 
1788: 
1789: The walls on either side of me became indistinguishable blurs of grey as we all but flew through the crooked alleyways of Cuzco with Hernando's soldiers ever close behind 
1790: 
1791: US. 
1792: 
1793: As we evaded our pursuers, every now and then we would see brigades of Spanish troops running through the streets, racing for the ramparts. 
1794: 
1795: We also—-I am ashamed to say—saw stakes not unlike those outside the city walls. They were set up in every one of the city's plazas, row after row of stakes, upon which were impaled the horribly mutilated bodies of captured Incan warriors. These warriors had had their hands, heads and genitals hacked off. 
1796: 
1797: In one such plaza, Renco saw an Incan longbow hanging from one of the desecrated corpses. He seized it and the quiver full of arrows on the ground beside it and then ducked back into the maze of alleyways. I just followed close behind him, not daring to let him out of my sight. 
1798: 
1799: At length, however, Renco turned abruptly and entered a building of some sort. It was a squat stone structure, remarkably solid. In fact, so solid it almost looked fortified. 
1800: 
1801: We passed through several outer rooms before we descended a flight of stone steps and came to a very large subterranean hall. 
1802: 
1803: 
1804: 
1805: The hall was divided into two levels—one wide lower 
1806: 
1807: and an upper landing that was little more than a balcony that ran around the circumference of the hall. 
1808: 
1809: But it was the lower storey that held my attention. 
1810: 
1811: There were nearly one hundred holes in the dirt floor of 
1812: 
1813: hall—pits over which a network of thin stone bridges 
1814: 
1815: With a surge of dread, I realised where we were. 
1816: 
1817: We were in an Incan dungeon. 
1818: 
1819: I was reminded of the fact that these Incans had not yet 
1820: 
1821: metallurgy, hence they had no bars to create A pit, I saw, was their answer to this dilemma. 
1822: 
1823: I looked up at the balcony that overlooked the lower It was a guard-walk, for the prison guards to patrol they looked down on the prisoners. 
1824: 
1825: Renco didn't miss a step. He just marched out onto one 
1826: 
1827: narrow stone bridges and peered down into the holes 
1828: 
1829: it. Wails and shouts erupted from below, from the 
1830: 
1831: starving prisoners who had been left in their pits the siege had begun a week earlier. 
1832: 
1833: Renco stopped above one of the pits. I followed him out the stone bridge and looked down into the dirty hole truly, this is what I saw. 
1834: 
1835: The pit itself must have been at least five paces deep, 
1836: 
1837: arthen walls. Escape was impossible. At the got- 
1838: 
1839: of the dirty well sat a man of average size, but filthy and putrid. Although he was thin, this man did not seem 
1840: 
1841: nor was he shouting like the rest of the poor, forlorn creatures in the prison hall. He just sat with his back pressed up against the wall of his pit, looking, if anything, relaxed and at ease. His composure that wanton coolness of criminals around the world—made my skin crawl. I wondered what Renco could want with such a character. 
1842: 
1843: 'Bassario,' said Renco. 
1844: 
1845: The criminal smiled. 'Why if it isn't the good prince Renco…' 
1846: 
1847: 'I need your help,' said Renco directly. 
1848: 
1849: The prisoner seemed to find this humorous. “I cannot imagine what the good prince could possibly want with my 
1850: 
1851: 
1852: 
1853: skills,” the criminal laughed. 'What is it, Renco? Now that your kingdom is in ruins are you thinking of embarking upon a life of crime?' 
1854: 
1855: Renco looked back toward the entrance to the under ground chamber, watching for Spaniards. I shared his concern. We had been in this dungeon too long already. 
1856: 
1857: 'I will only ask you this once, Bassario,' said Renco firmly. 
1858: 
1859: 'If you choose to help me, I will take you out of here. If you 
1860: 
1861: do not so choose, then I will leave you to die in this pit.' 
1862: 
1863: 'An interesting choice,' remarked the criminal. 
1864: 
1865: 'Well?' 
1866: 
1867: The criminal Bassario stood. 'Get me out of this hole.' 
1868: 
1869: Renco immediately went to fetch a wooden ladder rest ing against the far wall. 
1870: 
1871: For my part, I was worried about Hernando and his men. 
1872: 
1873: They could arrive at any moment and here Renco was bar gaining with a convict! I hurried over to the door through which we had entered the prison hall. When I got there I peered around the stone doorframe— 
1874: 
1875: —and saw the dark demon-like figure of Hernando Pizarro striding down the stairs toward me! 
1876: 
1877: My blood curdled at the sight—the wild brown eyes, the hooked black moustache, the scraggly black beard that had not been shaved for weeks. 
1878: 
1879: I whirled back inside the doorway and started running. 
1880: 
1881: 'Renco!' 
1882: 
1883: Renco had only just lowered the ladder into Bassario's pit when he turned and saw the first Spanish soldier come charging into the prison hall behind me. 
1884: 
1885: Renco's hands moved quickly and in an instant he had his longbow raised with an arrow drawn back to his ear. He let fly with the missile and it streaked across the room, careering right for my head. I ducked and the arrow smacked into the forehead of the soldier behind me. His feet flew out from under him and he was thrown to the floor in a heavy heap. 
1886: 
1887: I rushed out onto the network of stone bridges, ran quickly over the foul dungeon pits. 
1888: 
