8060: 
8061: Race had seen these guns before, but only in pictures, never in real life. 
8062: 
8063: They were Heckler & Koch G11s. 
8064: 
8065: 
8066: 
8067: According to Race's brother Marty, the Heckler & Koch G-11 was the most advanced assault rifle ever built. 
8068: 
8069: Designed and built in 1989, even now—ten years on—it was still twenty years ahead of its time. It was the Holy Grail of firearms as far as Marty had been concerned. 
8070: 
8071: It was the only production weapon in history to fire a caseless cartridge. Indeed, it was the only hand-held firearm in the world known to contain a microprocessor—principally because it was the only firearm in the world complex enough to require one. 
8072: 
8073: Due to the fact that it fired a caseless bullet, the G-11 was not only able to fire at the unimaginable rate of 2300 rounds per minute, it was also able to store in its body some 150 rounds—five times the number of bullets held in the clip of a.regular assault rifle like the M-16. And even then it was only half the size of an M-16. 
8074: 
8075: Truth be told, the only thing that had stopped the G-11 was money. In late 1989, political considerations forced the German government to rescind its deal with Heckler & Koch to use the G-11 in the Bundeswehr. 
8076: 
8077: As a result, only four hundred G-11s were ever made. 
8078: 
8079: Strangely, however, in an audit of the company during its takeover by Britain's Royal Ordnance only ten of that original batch were accounted for. 
8080: 
8081: The other three hundred and ninety guns had disappeared. 
8082: 
8083: I think we just found them, Race thought as he watched the rapas take flight in the face of the barrage of supermachine- gun fire coming at the guns. 
8084: 
