13109: Of course, Renco had planned it all, conceived it from the very beginning. 
13110: 
13111: I remembered our brief stop in the quarry town of Colco very early in our journey, remembered seeing Renco obtain a sack full of sharp-edged objects. And I distinctly remembered wondering at the time why we were wasting our precious time collecting rocks! 
13112: 
13113: But now I understood. 
13114: 
13115: Renco had obtained a collection of rocks from the quarry which had most imitated the strange black-and-purple stone from which the idol had been carved. 
13116: 
13117: Then he had given those stones to the criminal Bassario and commissioned him to carve an identical copy of the idol 
13118: 
13119: with which, presumably, he would bamboozle Hernando. 
13120: 
13121: It was brilliant. 
13122: 
13123: I also realised then what Bassario had been doing throughout our journey, at those times when he would skulk off to a corner of our camp and huddle over a small fire with his back to us. 
13124: 
13125: He had been carving his copy of the idol. 
13126: 
13127: And truly, it must be said, what a remarkable copy it was. 
13128: 
13129: The snarling jaws of the cat, the knife-like teeth. All of it carved out of a most lustrous kind of black-and-purple stone. 
13130: 
13131: And for a moment, all I could do was stare at the false idol and wonder what kind of master criminal Bassario had been. 
13132: 
13133: 
13134: 
13135: 'How long until you are finished?' Renco inquired of Has- sario. As Renco spoke, I noticed that the replica still required some finishing touches around the cat's jawline. 
13136: 
13137: 
13138: 
13139: 'Not long,' the criminal answered. 'It will be done by dawn.' 
13140: 
13141: 'You have half that time,' said Renco, turning away from Bassario and looking at the assembled group of survivors 
13142: 
13143: gathered behind him in the citadel. 
13144: 
13145: It did not give him much hope. 
13146: 
13147: Before him stood Vilcafor—-old and vain and frail—and seven Inca warriors, those who had been lucky enough to be inside the citadel when the rapas had first attacked. In addition to the seven warriors, however, Renco saw only an assortment 
13148: 
13149: of frightened-looking older men, women and children. 
13150: 
13151: 'Renco,' I whispered. 'What are we going to do?' 
13152: 
13153: My brave companion pursed his lips in thought. Then he spoke thusly: 'We are going to put an end to all this suffer ing. Once and for all.' 
13154: 
13155: 
13156: 
13157: And with that, while Bassario worked feverishly to finish his replica of the idol, Renco began to organise the surviv ing members of Vilcafor. 
13158: 
13159: 'Now listen,' said he as they gathered around him in a tight circle, 'the gold-eaters will be here by sunrise. By my reckoning, that gives us less than two hours to prepare for their arrival. 
13160: 
13161: 'Women, children and older kin—you will enter the quenko under the direction of my sister and get as far away from the village as possible. 
13162: 
13163: 'Warriors,' he said, turning to face the seven surviving warriors of the village. 'You will come with me, to this tem ple that Vilcafor speaks of. If these rapas come from within that building, then we will just have to put them back inside it. We shall lure them into the temple with the song of the wet idol and then we shall shut them back inside it. Now go, 
13164: 
13165: gather together whatever weapons you can muster.' 
13166: 
13167: The warriors hurried off. 
13168: 
13169: 'Lena,' said Renco. 
13170: 
13171: 'Yes, brother?' His beautiful sister appeared at his side. 
13172: 
13173: She smiled at me as she arrived, her eyes gleaming. 
13174: 
13175: 
13176: 
13177: 'I'll need the largest bladder you can find,“ said Renco. 
13178: 
13179: 'Filled with rainwater.' 
13180: 
13181: 'It will be done,' said Lena, hastening away. 
13182: 
13183: 'What about Hernando?' I inquired of Renco. 'What if he arrives while we are engaged in returning the rapas to their lair?' 
13184: 
13185: Said Renco, 'If, as my sister reports, he is following us with Chanca trackers, then as soon as he arrives here, he will know in which direction we have gone. Trust me, good Alberto, I am counting on such action. For when he finds me, he shall find an idol with me… and by my word, I shall give him that idol.' 
13186: 
13187: 'Hernando is a cold, callous man, Renco,' said I, 'vicious and remorseless. You cannot expect honour from him. Once 
13188: 
13189: you give him the idol, he will kill you for sure.' 
13190: 
13191: 'I know.' 
13192: 
13193: 'But then why—' 
13194: 
13195: 'My friend, what is the greater good?' said Renco softly. 
13196: 
13197: His face was kind, his voice calm. 'That I live and Hernando gets my people's idol? Or that I die and he gets a worthless replica of it?' 
13198: 
13199: He smiled at me. 'Personally, I would rather live, but I am afraid that there is more at stake here than just my life.' 
13200: 
13201: 
13202: 
13203: The citadel became a hive of activity as the people of Vilcafor went about preparing themselves for what was to come. 
13204: 
13205: Renco himself went off to brief the town's warriors more fully. As he did so, I took the opportunity to join Bassario for a short while and watch him fashion his replica of the idol. 
13206: 
13207: Truth be told—and God forgive me for this—I had an ulterior motive for speaking to him. 
13208: 
13209: 'Bassario,' I whispered hesitantly, 'does… does Lena have a husband?' 
13210: 
13211: Bassario shot me an impish grin. 'Why, monk, you old rascal, o .' said he in a full voice. 
13212: 
13213: I begged him in hushed tones not to speak so loudly. Has- sario, as one would expect of such a rogue, was highly amused. 
13214: 
13215: 'She once had a husband,' said he eventually. 'But their marriage ended many moons ago, before the arrival of gold- eaters. Lena's husband's name was Huarca and he was a promising young warrior, and their marriage insofar as an arranged marriage can bewas viewed as one of great promise. Little did anyone know, however, that Huarca was prone to fits of rage. After the birth of their son, Huarca began to beat Lena savagely. It was said that Lena would endure these beatings in order to protect Mani from his father's fury. Apparently she succeeded in this aim. Huarca never beat the boy once.' 
13216: 
13217: 'Why did she not leave him?' I inquired. 'After all, she is a princess of your people ' 
13218: 
13219: 
13220: 
13221: 'Huarca threatened to kill the boy if Lena told anyone about the beatings.' 
13222: 
13223: Good Lord, I thought. 
13224: 
13225: 'So what happened then?' I inquired. 
13226: 
13227: 'It was all uncovered by accident, really,' said Bassario. 
13228: 
13229: 'One day Renco called on Lena unexpectedly—-only to find her cowering in a corner of her home, cradling her son in her arms. She had tears in her eyes and her face was bloody and bruised. 
13230: 
13231: 'Huarca was captured immediately and sentenced to death. I believe he was ultimately dropped into a pit with a pair of hungry jungle cats. They tore him limb from limb.' 
13232: 
13233: Bassario shook his head. 'Monk, the man who beats his wife is the lowest form of coward—the lowest form. I should think Huarca met a fitting end.' 
13234: 
13235: 
13236: 
13237: I left Bassario to his work and repaired to a corner of the citadel to ready myself for the coming mission. 
13238: 
13239: After a short time, Renco joined me to do the same. He was still wearing the Spanish attire that he had stolen from the prison hulk many weeks ago—the brown leather vest, the white pantaloons, the knee-high leather boots. The extra clothing, he once told me, had been of immense value to him during our arduous trek through the rainforest. 
13240: 
13241: He slipped a quiver over his shoulder, began putting his 
13242: 
13243: sword belt on around his waist. 
13244: 
13245: 'Renco?' said I. 
13246: 
13247: 'Yes?' 
13248: 
13249: 'Why was Bassario in prison?' 
13250: 
13251: 'Ah, Bassario…' he sighed sadly. 
13252: 
13253: I waited for him to elaborate. 
13254: 
13255: 'Believe it or not, but Bassario was once a prince,' Renco said. 'A most esteemed young prince. Indeed, his father was no less than the Royal Stonemason, a brilliant builder and fashioner of stone, the most venerated engineer in the empire. Bassario was his son and prot6g6, and soon he too became a brilliant stonemason. Why, by the age of sixteen, 
13256: 
13257: 
13258: 
13259: he had surpassed his father in knowledge and skill, despite the fact that his father was the Royal Stonemason, the man who built citadels for the Sapa Inca! 
13260: 
13261: 'But Bassario was reckless. He was a brilliant sports- man—indeed as an archer he had no peer—but like many of his ilk, he was prone to drinking and gambling and disporting with the pretty young maidens of Cuzco's more raucous quarters. Unfortunately for him, however, his success with women was not mirrored at the gambling houses. He accumulated a monstrous debt with some less than reputable fellows. Then, when the debt became too great for him to repay, those rogues decided that Bassario would repay it another way—with his considerable talents.' 
13262: 
13263: 'How?' 
13264: 
13265: 'Bassario repaid them by using his brilliant stonemasonry 
13266: 
13267: skills to carve forgeries of famous statues and priceless treasures. Emerald or gold, silver or jade, whatever the substance, Bassario could replicate even the most complex object. 
13268: 
13269: 'Once he had copied a famous statue, his nefarious colleagues would break into the home of the real idol's owner 
13270: 
13271: and substitute Bassario's fake for the real one. 
13272: 
13273: 'Their scheme worked for almost a year and the criminals 
13274: 
13275: profited immensely from it until one day, Bassario's “friends” 
13276: 
13277: were discovered in the home of the Sapa Inca's cousin, caught in the act of switching a fake idol for the real one. 
13278: 
13279: 'Bassario's role in the scheme was soon uncovered. He 
13280: 
13281: was sent to prison and his entire family disgraced. His father was removed as Royal Stonemason and stripped of his titles. My brother, the Sapa Inca, decreed that Bassario's family were to be relocated from their home in the royal 
13282: 
13283: quarter to one of Cuzco's roughest slums.' 
13284: 
13285: I took this all in silently. 
13286: 
13287: Renco went on, 'I thought that the penalty was too harsh 
13288: 
13289: and told my brother so, but he wanted to make an example 
13290: 
13291: of Bassario and he ignored my pleas.' 
13292: 
13293: Renco gazed over at Bassario, working away in the corner of the citadel. 
13294: 
13295: 'Bassario was once a very noble young man. Flawed 
13296: 
13297: 
13298: 
13299: certainly, but essentially noble. That was why when it became my duty to rescue the idol from the Coricancha, I decided that I would use his talents to aid my quest. I reasoned that if the criminal elements of Cuzco could employ his skills to suit their own ends, then I most certainly could too, in my mission to rescue my people's Spirit.' 
13300: 
13301: 
13302: 
13303: At length Bassario finished his replica of the idol. 
13304: 
13305: When he was done, he brought the fake idol—together with the real one—over to Renco. 
13306: 
13307: Renco held both idols out in front of him. I looked at them over his shoulder and truly such was Bassario's skill that I could not tell which was the real one and which was the fraud. 
13308: 
13309: Bassario retired to his corner of the citadel and began gathering his things together—his sword, his quiver, his longbow. 
13310: 
13311: 'Where do you think you are going?' inquired Renco, seeing him stand. 
13312: 
13313: 'I'm leaving,' said Bassario simply. 
13314: 
13315: 'But I need your help,' said Renco. 'Vilcafor says that his men had to remove a great boulder from the temple's entrance and that it took ten men to do so. I am going to need as many 
13316: 
13317: . again if I am to roll it back into place. I need your help.' 
13318: 
13319: 'I feel that I have done more than my share in your quest, noble prince,' said Bassario. 'Escaping Cuzco, traversing the mountains, charging blindly through the perilous forests. 
13320: 
13321: And all the while making a fake idol for you. No, I have done my share, and now I am leaving.' 
13322: 
13323: 'Have you no loyalty to your people?' 
13324: 
13325: 'My people put me in jail, Renco,' Bassario retorted harshly. 'Then they punished my family for my crime—banished them to live in the filthiest, roughest quarter of Cuzco. 
13326: 
13327: My sister was molested in that slum, my father and mother beaten and robbed. The robbers even broke my father's fingers, so that he could no longer fashion stone. He was left to beg—to beg for scraps to feed his family. I have no grudge 
13328: 
13329: 
13330: 
13331: against my own punishment, no grudge at all, but then I also have no loyalty whatsoever to the society that punished my family for a crime that was mine and mine alone.' 
13332: 
13333: 'I am sorry' said Renco softly. “I did not know of these incidents. But please, Bassario, the idol, the Spirit of the People ' 
13334: 
13335: 'It is your quest, Renco. Not mine. I have done enough for you, more than enough. I think I have earned my freedom. 
13336: 
13337: Follow your own destiny and allow me to follow mine.' 
13338: 
13339: And with those sharp words, Bassario shouldered his longbow and climbed down into the quenko and disap peared into the darkness. 
13340: 
13341: / Renco did not attempt to stop him. He just looked after him, his face awash with sadness. 
13342: 
13343: 
13344: 
13345: Now it was that the rest of us were all prepared for our con frontation with the rapas. All that remained was one final touch. 
13346: 
13347: I picked up the small bladder of monkey urine that the toothless old man had given to me earlier that night and opened its cap. 
13348: 
13349: At once, an utterly vile odour assaulted my olfactory pas sages. I winced at the odour and despaired at the prospect of pouring the foul-smelling liquid over my body. 
13350: 
13351: But I did so nonetheless. And oh, how putrid it was! It was no wonder the rapas detested it. 
13352: 
13353: Renco chuckled at my discomfiture. Then he took the small bladder from me and began dousing himself in the stinking yellow liquid. The bladder was passed to the other warriors who would be venturing up into the mountains and the too, began bathing themselves in the foul, reeking liquid. 
13354: 
13355: As all was approaching readiness, Lena returned with a much larger animal bladder—a llama's bladder, I guessed— also filled with liquid. 
13356: 
13357: 'The rainwater you requested,' said she to Renco. 
13358: 
13359: 'Good,' Renco said, taking the llama's bladder from her. 
13360: 
13361: 'Then we are ready to go.” 
13362: 
13363: Renco poured a trickle of rainwater from the llama's blad der over the real idol. 
13364: 
13365: It hummed to life instantly, singing its melodious song. 
13366: 
13367: The interior of the citadel was empty. Lena had already sent the women, children and old folk of the village down into the quenko to commence their journey into its labyrinthine tunnels, a journey that would ultimately take them to the waterfall at the edge of the tableland. Lena herself had stayed behind in the citadel, ready to shut the doorstone after us. 
13368: 
13369: 'All right,' said Renco, nodding to the pair of Incan war riors manning the doorstone. 'Now.' 
13370: 
13371: At that moment, the two Incan warriors rolled the big 
13372: 
13373: stone aside, revealing the dark night outside. 
13374: 
13375: The rapas were right there! 
13376: 
13377: Waiting for us. 
13378: 
13379: Gathered in a wide circle immediately outside the citadel's stone doorframe. 
13380: 
13381: I counted twelve of them—twelve enormous black cats, each possessed of demonic yellow eyes, high pointed ears and powerful muscular shoulders. 
13382: 
13383: Renco held the singing idol out in front of him and the rapas stared at it, transfixed. 
13384: 
13385: Then, abruptly, the idol stopped its singing and equally suddenly, the rapas broke out of their trances and started a low growling. 
13386: 
13387: Renco quickly doused the idol with more water from the 
13388: 
13389: 
13390: 
13391: llama's bladder and the idol's song resumed and the rapas lapsed into their hypnosis once again. 
13392: 
13393: My heart also started beating again. 
13394: 
13395: Then, with the idol in his hands and the seven Incan war riors and myself in tow behind him, Renco stepped through the citadel's doorway and out into the cold night air. 
13396: 
13397: 
13398: 
13399: The rain had stopped—at long last—and the clouds had parted somewhat, revealing the starry night sky and a bril liant full moon. 
13400: 
13401: With flaming torches held high above our heads, we made our way through the village and onto a narrow path that ran alongside the river. 
13402: 
13403: The rapas were all around us, moving with slow, deliber ate steps, keeping their bodies low to the ground while at the same time keeping their eyes fixed on the singing idol in Renco's hands. 
13404: 
13405: My fear was extreme. Nay, it must be said that I have never been more terrified in my life. 
13406: 
13407: To be surrounded by a pack of such enormous, danger ous creaturesreatures totally devoid of pity or mercy, creatures that killed without the slightest hesitation. 
13408: 
13409: They were so big! In the flickering firelight of our torches the muscles on their shoulders and flanks rippled orange. 
13410: 
13411: Their breathing was loud too—a kind of deep-chested bray ing sound not unlike that of a horse. 
13412: 
13413: As we walked along the riverside path, I looked behind me and saw Lena standing at the edge of the village holding a torch, watching after us. 
13414: 
13415: After a few moments, however, she vanished from my view—having decided, I imagined, to go back to the citadel and carry out her duties there. We continued on our journey up to the mysterious temple. 
13416: 
13417: 
13418: 
13419: Along the path we went. Nine men—Renco, myself and the seven Incan warriors—surrounded by the pack of rapas. 
13420: 
13421: 
13422: 
13423: We came to the mountainside, to a narrow passageway set into the rockface. One of the Incan warriors told Renco that the temple was to be found at the other end of this passageway. 
13424: 
13425: Renco doused the idol once again. It sang loudly, its high- pitched tone cutting through the early-morning air. Then he entered the passageway, the cats trailing close behind him like children following a schoolteacher. 
13426: 
13427: As we walked down the narrow passageway by the light of our flaming torches, one of the Incan warriors foolishly attempted to stab one of the entranced rapas with the point of his spear—but just as he was about to drive his weapon into the beast's flank, the rapa turned on him and snarled ferociously, stopping him in mid-lunge. The big cat then just turned forward and resumed its enraptured pursuit of the singing idol. 
13428: 
13429: The warrior exchanged a glance with one of his companions. 
13430: 
13431: The rapas might have been entranced, but they were not totally defenceless. 
13432: 
13433: Now it was that we emerged from the narrow passageway into a wide circular canyon of some kind. As the chieftain Vilcafor had said, a most incredible finger of stone shot up out of the middle of it, soaring high into the night sky. 
13434: 
13435: A path was cut into the canyon wall to our left—the .escape path Vilcafor had ordered his people to build. It curled around the circumference of the cylindrical canyon, spiralling up and around the finger of stone in its centre. 
13436: 
13437: Renco mounted the path, stepping slowly upward, holding the wet idol in his hands. The cats followed him. The Incan warriors and myself walked slowly up the path behind them. 
13438: 
13439: Up and up we went. Round and round, following the steady curve of the path. 
13440: 
13441: At length we came to a rope bridge that stretched out over the canyon, connecting the outer path to the finger of stone in the middle of the great canyon. 
13442: 
13443: I looked out across the ravine at the stone tower opposite 
13444: 
13445: me. 
13446: 
13447: 
13448: 
13449: On top of the tower, surrounded by some low-cut foliage, I saw a magnificent stepped pyramid not unlike those found in the lands of the Aztecas. A box-shaped tabernacle was mounted atop the imposing triangular pyramid. 
13450: 
13451: Renco crossed the bridge first. The cats followed him, one by one, bouncing with supreme surefootedness across the long swooping bridge. The warriors went next. I crossed last of all. 
13452: 
13453: Once I had navigated my way across the bridge, I mounted a series of wide stone steps which opened onto a clearing of some sort. At the head of this clearing lay the portal to the temple, the entrance. 
13454: 
13455: Wide and dark, square and menacing, it yawned open as if daring all the world to enter. 
13456: 
13457: With the wet idol in his hands, Renco approached the portal. 'Warriors,' said he and firmly, 'man the boulder.' 
13458: 
13459: The seven warriors and my humble self hurried over to the boulder that stood to the side of the temple's yawning entryway. 
13460: 
13461: Renco stood in the mouth of the portal, dousing the idol with rainwater, causing it to continue its melodious song. 
13462: 
13463: The cats stood before him, staring at the singing idol, hypnotised. 
13464: 
13465: Renco took a step inside the temple. 
13466: 
13467: The cats followed him. 
13468: 
13469: Renco took another step down and the first cat went inside after him. 
13470: 
13471: Another step. 
13472: 
13473: A second cat, then a third, then a fourth. 
13474: 
13475: At which stage Renco tipped as much water as was left inside the llama's bladder over the idol, and then—after taking a final solemn glance at his people's most prized possession—he hurled it down into the dark depths of the temple. 
13476: 
13477: The cats leapt inside the temple after it. All twelve of them. 
13478: 
13479: 'Quickly, the boulder!“ Renco cried, hurrying out of the temple's entrance. 'Push it back into the portal!' 
13480: 
13481: 
13482: 
13483: We pushed as one. 
13484: 
13485: The boulder rumbled against the threshold. 
13486: 
13487: I leaned on it with all my might, straining against the weight of the great stone. Renco appeared beside me, also heaving against it. 
13488: 
13489: The boulder moved slowly back into the portal. A few more paces to go. 
13490: 
13491: Almost there… 
13492: 
13493: Just a couple.., more… 
13494: 
13495: 'Renco,' a voice said suddenly from somewhere nearby. 
13496: 
13497: It was a woman's voice. 
13498: 
13499: Renco and I turned together. 
13500: 
13501: And we saw Lena standing at the edge of the clearing. 
13502: 
13503: 'Lena?' Renco said. 'What are you doing up here? I thought I asked you to—' 
13504: 
13505: At that moment, Lena was shoved roughly aside, thrown to the ground, and suddenly I saw a man standing on the stone steps behind her, and in that single, solitary instant, every ounce of blood in my veins turned to ice. 
13506: 
13507: I was looking at Hernando Pizarro. 
13508: 
13509: 
13510: 
13511: A stream of about twenty conquistadors poured out from the foliage behind Lena and spread out around the clearing, their muskets raised and pointed at our faces. The firelight of their torches illuminated the entire clearing. 
13512: 
13513: They were accompanied by three olive-skinned natives who each had long, sharp spikes of bone protruding from their cheeks. Chancas. The Chanca trackers Hernando had employed to follow our trail to Vilcafor. 
13514: 
13515: Last of all—nay, most ominously of all—came another olive-skinned man. He was taller than the others, bigger, with a long shock of matted black hair that came down to his shoulders. He also had a spike of bone thrust through his left cheek. 
13516: 
13517: It was Castino. The brutish Chanca who had been in the same prison hulk as Renco at the beginning of our adven ture, the one who had overheard Renco say that the idol was in the Coricancha in Cuzco. 
13518: 
13519: The conquistadors and the Chancas formed a wide circle around Renco, myself and the seven Incan warriors. 
13520: 
13521: It was then that I noticed how filthy they all looked. To a man, the conquistadors were covered in mud and grime. And they looked worn and exhausted, weary beyond measure. 
13522: 
13523: Whence I realised—this was all that remained of Her- nando's hundred-strong legion. On their march through the mountains and the forests, Hernando's men had died all around him. From disease, from starvation, or just from sheer exhaustion. 
13524: 
13525: 
13526: 
13527: This was all that remained of his legion. Twenty men. 
13528: 
13529: Hernando stepped forward, yanking Lena to her feet as he did so. Dragging her behind him, he approached the temple and stood before Renco, staring imperiously down at him. Hernando was a full head taller than Renco and twice as broad. He shoved Lena roughly into Renco's arms. 
13530: 
13531: For my part, I cast a fearful glance at the temple's portal. 
13532: 
13533: It was still partially open, the gap between the boulder and the great stone doorway easily wide enough for a rapa to fit through. 
13534: 
13535: This was not good. 
13536: 
13537: If the water drained off the idol and it stopped its song, the rapas would break out of their spells and- 
13538: 
13539: 'At last we meet,' said Hernando to Renco in Spanish. 
13540: 
13541: 'You have evaded me for far too long, young prince. You will die slowly.' 
13542: 
13543: Renco said nothing. 
13544: 
13545: 'And you, monk,' said Hernando, rounding on me. 'You are a traitor to your country and to your God. You will die even more slowly.' 
13546: 
13547: I swallowed back my fear. 
13548: 
13549: Hernando turned back to Renco. 'The idol. Give it to me.' 
13550: 
13551: Renco didn't flinch. He just slowly reached into the pouch on his belt and extracted the false idol. 
13552: 
13553: Hernando's eyes lit up as he saw it. If I didn't know better, I would have sworn he began to salivate. 
13554: 
13555: 'Give it to me,' said he. 
13556: 
13557: Renco stepped forward. 
13558: 
13559: 'On your knees.' 
13560: 
13561: Slowly, despite the sheer humiliation that attended it, Renco knelt down and offered the idol to the standing Hernando. 
13562: 
13563: Hernando took it from him, his eyes gleaming with greed as he stared at his long-sought-after prize. 
13564: 
13565: After a few moments, he glanced up from the idol and turned to one of his men. 
13566: 
13567: 
13568: 
13569: 'Sergeant,' he said. 
13570: 
13571: 'Yes, sir?” the sergeant standing nearest to him replied. 
13572: 
13573: 'Execute them.' 
13574: 
13575: 
13576: 
13577: My hands were bound together with a long length of rope. 
13578: 
13579: Renco's were too. 
13580: 
13581: Lena was snatched away from Renco by two of the Spanish soldiers, and the two brutes goaded her with foul utterings of what they would do to her once Renco and I were dead, utterings which I dare not repeat here. 
13582: 
13583: Renco and I were made to kneel before a large rectangu lar stone in the middle of the clearing, a stone that looked like a low altar. 
13584: 
13585: The Spanish sergeant stood over me, his sabre drawn. 
13586: 
13587: 'You, Chanca,' said Hernando, tossing a sword to Castino. Ever since he had arrived in the clearing, the vile Chanca had been eyeing Renco with pure unadulterated hatred. 'You may dispose of the prince.' 
13588: 
13589: 'Gladly,' said Castino in Spanish, catching the sword and marching quickly over to the altar stone. 
13590: 
13591: 'Cut their hands off first,' said Hernando judiciously. 'I would like to hear them scream before they die.' 
13592: 
13593: Our two executioners nodded as two more conquistadors pulled Renco and myself into position—yanking on our bonds so that our arms were stretched out across the wide altar. Our wrists were now totally exposed, our hands ready to be excised from our bodies. 
13594: 
13595: “Alberto,' said Renco softly. 
13596: 
13597: 'Yes.' 
13598: 
13599: 'My friend, before we die, I would like you to know that it has been an honour and a joy to have known you. What you have done for my people will be remembered for gen erations. For that I thank you.' 
13600: 
13601: 'My brave friend,' I replied, 'if the circumstances were to repeat themselves, I would do it all again. May God look after you in heaven.' 
13602: 
13603: 'And you too,' said Renco. 'And you too.' 
13604: 
13605: 
13606: 
13607: 'Gentlemen,' said Hernando to our executioners. 
13608: 
13609: 'Remove their hands.' 
13610: 
13611: The sergeant and the Chanca raised their glistening 
13612: 
13613: swords at the same time, raised them high above their heads. 
13614: 
13615: 'Wait!' someone called suddenly. 
13616: 
13617: At that moment, one of the other conquistadors hurried over to the altar. He appeared older than his fellow sol- diers-more grizzled—a wily old fox of a man. He ran directly over to Renco. 
13618: 
13619: He had spied the emerald pendant looped around my companion's neck. 
13620: 
13621: The old conquistador quickly lifted the leather necklace over Renco's head, smiling greedily at him as he did so. 
13622: 
13623: 'Thank you, savage,' he sneered as he placed the emerald pendant around his own neck and scurried back to his posi tion over by the temple's portal. 
13624: 
13625: Our two executioners looked over to Hernando for the signal. 
13626: 
13627: But strangely, Hernando wasn't watching them anymore. 
13628: 
13629: In fact, he wasn't even looking at Renco or myself either. 
13630: 
13631: He was just staring off to our right—at the temple—his mouth agape. 
13632: 
13633: I spun to see what it was he was looking at. 
13634: 
13635: 'Oh, my Lord…' I breathed. 
13636: 
13637: 
13638: 
13639: One of the rapas was standing in the half-opened mouth of the portal, peering curiously at the assembled mass of humanity before it 
13640: 
13641: It loomed large in the doorway—its powerful forelimbs splayed wide, its shoulders bunched with muscle—but its appearance at that moment was oddly comical, chiefly 
13642: 
13643: because it was holding something in its mouth. 
13644: 
13645: It was the idol. 
13646: 
13647: The real idol. 
13648: 
13649: The great black cat—previously so terrifying and vicious—now looked like a humble retriever bringing a stick back to its owner. Indeed, the rapa just held the idol 
13650: 
13651: 
13652: 
13653: dumbly in its mouth, as if it were looking for someone who might wet it again and thus make it sing. 
13654: 
13655: Hernando just gazed at the cat—-or rather, at the idol that it held between its mighty jaws. And then, all of a sudden, his eyes swept from the rapa and the idol in its mouth to the idol that he held in his own hands, and from it to Renco and 
13656: 
13657: myself, a wash of understanding spreading across his face. 
13658: 
13659: He knew. 
13660: 
13661: He knew that he had been deceived. 
13662: 
13663: The big Spaniard's face went red with fury as he glared at Renco and me. 
13664: 
13665: 'Kill them!” he roared to our executioners. 'Kill them 
13666: 
13667: now!' 
13668: 
13669: 
13670: 
13671: It was at that exact moment that a myriad of things happened at once. 
13672: 
13673: Our executioners raised their swords again—re-aimed at our necks now—and had just begun to bring their blades down in two great swinging arcs when abruptly a sharp whistling sound cut through the air above my head. 
13674: 
13675: Not a moment later, with a powerful thud, an arrow lodged itself in the nose of my executioner, sending a garish fountain of blood exploding from his face and hurling him clear off his feet. 
13676: 
13677: For its part, the rapa in the portal—after seeing the crowd of people standing in the clearing before it and sensing another tasty human meal—immediately dropped the idol from its mouth and leapt ferociously at the nearest Spaniard, not a moment before the eleven other rapas rushed out from within the temple one after the other after the other—and commenced their own attack on the crowd of conquistadors. 
13678: 
13679: Castino had seen the other executioner drop to the ground beside him, struck by the arrow, and had momen tarily halted his lunge at Renco's neck, a look of stunned incomprehension on his face. 
13680: 
13681: I knew what he was thinking. 
13682: 
13683: Who had fired the arrow? And from where? 
13684: 
13685: Castino obviously decided he would answer these ques tions later, after he had killed Renco. 
13686: 
13687: He quickly raised his blade again and brought it down with tremendous force— 
13688: 
13689: 
13690: 
13691: —whence another arrow slammed into his sword's hilt and sent it flying from his grasp. 
13692: 
13693: Not a moment later, a third arrow whistled down from somewhere above us and struck the rope binding Renco's hands together, cutting it cleanly in two, releasing him. 
13694: 
13695: Renco immediately leapt to his feet, just as Castino—now swordless—-swung at him with one of his gigantic fists. Renco quickly yanked the conquistador who had been holding him to the altar in between himself and the oncoming blow, and Castino's mighty knuckles hit the conquistador square in the face, shattering his nose in an instant, pummelling it into the back of his skull, killing him with a single blow! 
13696: 
13697: Just then another conquistador levelled his musket at Renco and fired at exactly the same time as Renco pivoted on the spot—bringing the dead conquistador around in front of him, using him as a shield—and the musket's shot opened up a ragged red hole in the centre of the dead soldier's chest. 
13698: 
13699: As Renco went off to join the fight, the conquistador holding my wrists across the altar drew his sword and glared at me with evil intent. 
13700: 
13701: But thenmfaster than a man can blink—an arrowhead exploded out from the centre of his face and the conquistador flopped down onto the altar stone in front of me, face-down, an arrow sticking out from the back of his head. 
13702: 
13703: I looked up into the darkness beyond him, searching for 
13704: 
13705: the source of the arrows. 
13706: 
13707: And I saw him. 
13708: 
13709: Saw the figure of a man positioned up on the rim of the canyon. 
13710: 
13711: He was silhouetted against the moon, crouched on one knee with a longbow extended in the firing position and an 
13712: 
13713: arrow drawn back to his ear. 
13714: 
13715: It was Bassario! 
13716: 
13717: I gave a cheer, and then I immediately set about unravelling my bonds. 
13718: 
13719: 
13720: 
13721: It cannot be understated the carnage that was going on around me at this time. It was-mayhem. Pure and utter mayhem. The clearing in front of the temple had become a battlefield—a ferocious, bloody battlefield. 
13722: 
13723: Fighting went on everywhere, in about a dozen separate battles. 
13724: 
13725: Over by the temple, the rapas had already killed five of the conquistadors, and now they were attacking four more Spaniards and their three Chanca trackers. 
13726: 
13727: Elsewhere in the clearing, the seven Incan warriors— avoided by the rapas due to the monkey urine that covered their bodies—fought with the remaining Spaniards. Some of them fell as the conquistadors fired their muskets into them, others hacked into their Spanish foes with rocks or stones or whatever weapons they could lay their hands on. Despite all the murder and bloodshed that I had seen on my travels throughout New Spain, this was indeed the most brutal and primal example of combat that I had ever witnessed. 
13728: 
13729: Beside me, Renco and Castino had both picked up swords and were now engaged in the most ferocious of swordfights. 
13730: 
13731: Castino, taller than my brave companion by at least two heads, held his sword two-handed and unleashed upon Renco a rain of powerful blows. 
13732: 
13733: But Renco parried well-done-handed, just as I had taught 
13734: 
13735: “him—dancing backwards in the mud like a classical Span ish fencer, maintaining his balance as he retreated toward the foliage. 
13736: 
13737: As I finally released the rope from my left wrist and stood, I realised just what a keen student Renco had been. It was 
13738: 
13739: clear to me now that the pupil by far outclassed the teacher. 
13740: 
13741: His swordsmanship was dazzling. 
13742: 
13743: For every mighty blow that Castino threw at him, Renco would quickly bring up his sword—just in time to stop it. 
13744: 
13745: The two men's swords clashed with ferocious intensity. 
13746: 
13747: Castino swung, Renco parried. Castino lunged, Renco danced. 
13748: 
13749: And then Castino unleashed a devilish blow, a blow so 
13750: 
13751: 
13752: 
13753: hard and swift that it would have taken the head off any ordinary man. 
13754: 
13755: But not Renco. 
13756: 
13757: His reflexes were too quick. He ducked under the blow and in the fleeting instant that followed, he leapt forward, up o.nto a low rock and launched himself into the air, negating the height difference between himself and Castino, his blade cutting through the air so swiftly it whistled, and before I even knew what was happening, I saw his sword embedded horizontally in the tree trunk behind Castino's neck. 
13758: 
13759: Castino just stood there, his mouth hanging open, his eyes wide. A moment later, his sword dropped out of his hand. 
13760: 
13761: And then abruptly his entire body just dropped away from beneath his ugly head. 
13762: 
13763: Renco had cut his head clean off his shoulders! 
13764: 
13765: I almost cheered. 
13766: 
13767: 
13768: 
13769: Which is to say I would have cheered, had I not had other things with which to deal. 
13770: 
13771: I spun to survey the battlefield around me. 
13772: 
13773: Small battles were still being waged all over the clear- 
13774: 
13775: ing—but the only obvious victors seemed to be the rapas. 
13776: 
13777: It was then that I saw the idol. 
13778: 
13779: The real idol. 
13780: 
13781: It lay on the threshold of the portal, tilted over onto its side, at the exact spot where it had fallen from the rapa's mouth earlier. 
13782: 
13783: With the length of rope still tied to my right wrist—it was about two paces long—I grabbed a sword and a torch from the ground beside me and ran for the temple, through the clashing of blades and the screams of the ravaged conquis tadors. 
13784: 
13785: I reached the portal and fell to the ground next to the idol, grabbed it- 
13786: 
13787: -just as one of the Spanish soldiers rammed into me from behind, bowling both of us in through the portal and into the temple! 
13788: 
13789: 
13790: 
13791: The two of us tumbled down a set of wide stone steps, down into the darkness of the temple, a tangled mix of arms, legs, idol and torch. 
13792: 
13793: We hit the bottom of the stairs and fell apart. We were inside a dark stone-walled tunnel of some sort. 
13794: 
13795: My foe clambered to his feet first so that he now stood against the wall, in front of a small alcove set into it. I was still sprawled out on the floor, flat on my behind, with the idol sitting in my lap. 
13796: 
13797: As the Spanish soldier stood over me, I saw the emerald necklace looped around his neck and I recognised him instantly. He was the wily older soldier who had relieved Renco of his priceless pendant earlier. 
13798: 
13799: The old fox drew his sword, raised it high. I was defenceless, completely exposed. 
13800: 
13801: At that moment, with an obscenely loud roar, something very large leapt over my head from behind and rammed 
13802: 
13803: into the conquistador at frightening speed. 
13804: 
13805: A rapa. 
13806: 
13807: The cat hit the Spaniard with such colossal force that he was thrown back into the alcove behind him. His head struck the wall with the most sickening of sounds and just exploded, cracking like an egg, a foul spray of blood and brains shooting out from the hole that was instantaneously created in the back of his skull. 
13808: 
13809: The wily old soldier collapsed into the alcove, but he was well and truly dead by the time he reached the floor. 
13810: 
13811: The cat began to ravage him on the spot, its tail licking back and forth behind its body as it did so. 
13812: 
13813: I seized the moment, grabbed hold of the idol and charged back up the stairs, out of the temple. 
13814: 
13815: 
13816: 
13817: I burst out into the night, thankful to have escaped death once again. 
13818: 
13819: But my revelry was shortlived. No sooner was I out of the portal than I heard a sharp click-click from somewhere behind me, followed quickly by a coarse shout of 'Monk!' 
13820: 
13821: 
13822: 
13823: I spun. 
13824: 
13825: And saw Hernando Pizarro standing before me with a pistol in his hand, levelled right at my chest. 
13826: 
13827: Then, before I could so much as move, I saw a flash of fire flare out from the end of the pistol, heard its loud report echo out all around me, and almost immediately I felt a tremendous weight slam into my chest and I was thrown backwards. 
13828: 
13829: I collapsed to the ground instantly, after which I saw nothing but clouds—dark storm clouds rolling across the starry night sky above meL and it was at that moment that I realised to my extreme horror that I had just been shot. 
13830: 
13831: 
13832: 
13833: I lay on my back, my teeth clenched in agony, looking up at the cloud-strewn sky, a searing, burning pain shooting through my chest. 
13834: 
13835: Hernando bent over me and took the idol from my loose grasp. As he did so, he slapped me lustily across the face and said, 'Die slowly, monk.” Then he was gone. 
13836: 
13837: I lay on the stone steps in front of the temple, waiting for the life to drain out of me, waiting for the pain to become unbearable. 
13838: 
13839: But then for some reason that was beyond my ken, my strength, rather than fading, began to return. 
13840: 
13841: The searing pain in my chest subsided and I sat up instantly and patted my chest at the point where the bullet 
13842: 
13843: had created a hole in my cloak. 
13844: 
13845: I felt something there. 
13846: 
13847: Something soft and thick and square. I extracted it from my cloak. 
13848: 
13849: It was my Bible. 
13850: 
13851: My three-hundred-page, handwritten, leather-bound Bible. 
13852: 
13853: In the centre of it was a tattered round hole that looked like the burrow of a worm. At the farthest extremity of the 
13854: 
13855: burrow I saw a warped sphere of dull grey lead. 
13856: 
13857: Hernando's bullet. 
13858: 
13859: My Bible had stopped his bullet! 
13860: 
13861: Praised be the Word of the Lord. 
13862: 
13863: I leapt to my feet, exhilarated in the moment. I looked for 
13864: 
13865: 
13866: 
13867: my sword, couldn't find it anywhere, gazed out over the clearing. 
13868: 
13869: I saw Renco on the far side of the clearing, fighting with two swords against two sabre-wielding conquistadors. 
13870: 
13871: Two Incan warriors grappled with a pair of Spaniards not far from where I stood—they seemed to be the only other men left alive on the rock tower 
13872: 
13873: And then I saw Hernando—with the idol in his hands— hurrying away into the foliage to my right, dashing down 
13874: 
13875: the stone stairway there. 
13876: 
13877: My eyes went wide. 
13878: 
13879: He was going for the rope bridge. 
13880: 
13881: If he got there, he would almost certainly cut the bridge and leave us stranded on the tower, stranded with the rapas. 
13882: 
13883: I hurried after him, bounding across the clearing, hur dling a rapa as it lay on the ground tearing into the body of a dead conquistador. 
13884: 
13885: I flew down the stone steps two at a time, my heart racing, my legs pounding, chasing after Hernando. As I rounded a bend in the stairs, I saw him about ten paces in front of me, stepping out onto the rope bridge. 
13886: 
13887: Hernando was large and muscular, and he moved as such. I was smaller, more nimble, faster. I gained on him quickly and dashed out onto the bridge after him, at which moment, with absolutely nothing else to call on, I hurled myself—swordless—at his back. 
13888: 
13889: I collided with him most heavily and we fell together onto the thin floorboards of the rope bridge, high above the canyon floor. 
13890: 
13891: But such was the weight of our landing that the floor boards beneath us shattered like twigs and to my utter horror we fell straight through them, down into the abyss… 
13892: 
13893: 
13894: 
13895: But our fall was brief. 
13896: 
13897: With a sudden, jarring jolt the two of us came to an abrupt halt. In the terror of our fall, Hernando had reached out for a handhold, had grasped for anything that would stop his fall. 
13898: 
13899: 
13900: 
13901: What he had found was the free end of the rope that was still tied to my right wrist. Now the rope lay stretched over a lone floorboard on the rope bridge, with Hernando and myself dangling from both of its extremities! 
13902: 
13903: And so we hung there like counterweights hanging from a pulley, at different ends of the same rope, with dangling cords of the partially-broken rope bridge hanging down all around us. 
13904: 
13905: Through force of luck—bad luck in my caseI hung below Hernando, my head down near his dangling knees. 
13906: 
13907: Hernando hung up higher, just below the remaining floor boards of the bridge. 
13908: 
13909: I saw that he had the idol in his left hand, while he held onto my rope with his right. He reached up with his left hand, trying desperately to loop the idol over the rope bridge's surviving floorboards and garner a handhold. 
13910: 
13911: Once he succeeded in doing that, I realised, he would be safe to let me fall. At present, my weight—small though it 
13912: 
13913: was compared to his—was the only thing holding him up. 
13914: 
13915: I had to do something. And quickly. 
13916: 
13917: 'Why are you doing this, monk!' Hernando roared as he reached for his salvation, so close now. 'What do you care about this idol! I would kill for it!' 
13918: 
13919: As he raged, I saw one of the thin cords dangling down . from the rope bridge above us-one of the cords that had 
13920: 
13921: previously held up the bridge's handrail. 
13922: 
13923: If I could just… 
13924: 
13925: 'You would kill for it, would you, Hernando?' said I, try ing to distract him as I endeavoured to untie the length of rope that was tied around my right wrist—the rope that connected me to Hernando. 'That means nothing to me!' 
13926: 
13927: 'No?' he shouted. It was a race now, a race to see who would get to his objective first—Hernando to the floorboard above us, me to untie the rope that joined us together. 
13928: 
13929: 'No!“ I called back—just as I succeeded in releasing 
13930: 
13931: myself from the length of rope. 
13932: 
13933: 'Why, monk?' 
13934: 
13935: 'Because, Hernando, I would die for it.' 
13936: 
13937: 
13938: 
13939: And with that, having now freed myself from the rope tied to my wrist, I reached out for the thin cord dangling down from the bridge above me and grabbed hold of while at exactly the same moment I released my grip on the 
13940: 
13941: length of rope connecting me to Hernando. 
13942: 
13943: The response was instantaneous. 
13944: 
13945: With the counterweight at the other end of his rope now gone, Hernando fell. Straight down. 
13946: 
13947: He fell past me, his body a streaking blur of screaming humanity, and as a fitting final insult, as he whistled by in front of me, I reached out and plucked the idol from his grasp. 
13948: 
13949: 'Noooooo!' Hernando screamed as he fell. 
13950: 
13951: And as I hung there above the abyss—dangling one- handed from the rope bridge's cord, holding the sacred idol in my free hand—I watched the look of absolute terror on his face get smaller and smaller until, finally, it disappeared into the dark abyss beneath me and soon all I could hear was his screaming. 
13952: 
13953: It would stop a moment later at the same time as I heard a distant, sickening splat. 
13954: 
13955: 
13956: 
13957: I arrived back in the clearing some time later, the idol in my hand. 
13958: 
13959: The sight which greeted me was like a glimpse of the underworld itself. 
13960: 
13961: In the flickering light of the torches that littered the clearing, I saw the rapas kneeling over the ranks of dead conquistadors, gorging themselves on fresh human flesh. 
13962: 
13963: Pointed silver helmets lay strewn everywhere, glinting in the firelight. 
13964: 
13965: It was then that I saw Renco and Lena and three of the Incan warriors standing over by the portal, holding swords and muskets in their hands—the only survivors of the car nage, thanks largely to their fighting skills and the layer of 
13966: 
13967: monkey urine that covered them. They appeared to be 
13968: 
13969: “ searching for something. The idol no doubt. 
13970: 
13971: 'Renco!' I called. 'Lena!' 
13972: 
13973: I regretted it as soon as I did it. 
13974: 
13975: One of the rapas lying on the ground in front of me immediately looked up from his feasting, disturbed by my shout. 
13976: 
13977: The massive beast rose to its feet, glared at me. 
13978: 
13979: Another cat beyond it did the same. 
13980: 
13981: Then another, and another. 
13982: 
13983: The pack of giant cats formed a wide circle around me. 
13984: 
13985: They held their heads low, their ears pinned back. 
13986: 
13987: I saw Renco turn and see my predicament. But he was too far away to be of any help. 
13988: 
13989: 
13990: 
13991: I wondered why my own layer of monkey urine was no 
13992: 
13993: longer keeping the cats at bay. Perhaps it had been scraped away during my scuffle with the wily old conquistador inside the temple or maybe it had rubbed off when I had fallen to the ground after being shot by Hernando. 
13994: 
13995: Whatever the case, I thought, this was it, this was the 
13996: 
13997: end. 
13998: 
13999: The lead rapa tensed its whole body, prepared itself to 
14000: 
14001: pounce. And then— 
14002: 
14003: 
14004: 
14005: —the first drop of water hit the top of my head with a loud smack. It was closely followed by a second drop and then a third, then a fourth. 
14006: 
14007: And then, like a gift from God himself, the skies parted and the rain came tumbling down. 
14008: 
14009: Oh, how it rained! It came down in sheets—thick drenching sheets—big fat drops of water hammering down on the rock tower with tremendous force, smacking down against my head, smacking down against the idol. 
14010: 
14011: And at that moment, thank the Lord, the idol began to sing. 
14012: 
14013: 
14014: 
14015: Its song becalmed the cats instantly. 
14016: 
14017: They all just peered at the dripping idol in my hands, their heads cocked to one side in response to its melodious high-pitched hum. 
14018: 
14019: Renco, Lena and the three warriors came over to where I stood, shielding their torches against the rain, skirting around the pack of entranced rapas. 
14020: 
14021: I noticed that Renco held Bassario's fake idol in his hand. 
14022: 
14023: 'Thank you, Alberto,' said he, taking the singing idol from me. 'I think I shall take that now.' 
14024: 
14025: Beside him, Lena smiled at me, her beautiful olive skin sparkling in the rainstorm. 'So, you defeated the big gold- eater to save our idol,' she said. 'Is there anything you cannot do, my brave little hero?' 
14026: 
14027: 
14028: 
14029: As she said these words, she suddenly leaned forward 
14030: 
14031: and kissed me softly on the lips. My heart almost skipped a 
14032: 
14033: beat as her lips pressed themselves firmly against mine. My 
14034: 
14035: knees felt weak. I almost fell over, so delightful was the 
14036: 
14037: touch of her lips. 
14038: 
14039: 
14040: 
14041: As Lena was kissing me so beautifully, however, a voice 
14042: 
14043: from somewhere behind me said: 'Come now, monk. I 
14044: 
14045: thought that wasn't allowed for men of your ilk.' 
14046: 
14047: I turned to see Bassario standing on the stone steps 
14048: 
14049: behind me, his longbow slung over his shoulder, his face 
14050: 
14051: creased into a broad smile. 
14052: 
14053: 'We reserve the right to make exceptions,' said I. 
14054: 
14055: Bassario laughed. 
14056: 
14057: Renco turned to face him. 'Thank you for returning to 
14058: 
14059: help us, Bassario. Your arrows saved our lives. What made 
14060: 
14061: you return?' 
14062: 
14063: Bassario shrugged. 'As I reached the waterfall at the end of 
14064: 
14065: the quenko, I saw the gold-eaters approaching from the other 
14066: 
14067: side of the river. Then I supposed that if by some miracle you 
14068: 
14069: survived all of this, people would sing songs about you. I 
14070: 
