14161: 
14162: 
14163: It has now been many years since those events transpired. 
14164: 
14165: Now I am an old man, withered and frail, seated at a desk in a monastery, writing by the light of a candle. Snow- covered mountains stretch away from me in every direction. 
14166: 
14167: The mountains of the Pyrenees. 
14168: 
14169: After Renco entered the temple with the two idols and the rapas, Bassario, Lena and I returned to Vilcafor. 
14170: 
14171: It was not long before word spread throughout the empire of our deeds—word of Hernando's death, and of the idol being laid to rest inside a mysterious temple in the presence of a pack of deadly rapas. 
14172: 
14173: Typically, the Spanish colonial government created some sham tale about the death of the Governor's brother, Her- nando. They said that he died honourably at the hands of an unknown tribe of natives while he had been bravely navigating some uncharted jungle river. If only my countrymen knew the truth. 
14174: 
14175: I also understand that the Incas did indeed sing songs about our adventureand, yes, those songs mentioned Has- sario's nameand the singing of those ballads continued even after the Spanish conquest of their lands. 
14176: 
14177: The gold-eaters, they said, could seize their land, burn their houses, torture and murder their people. 
14178: 
14179: But they could not take their spirit. 
14180: 
14181: 
14182: 
14183: To this day, I do not know what Renco did inside that temple with the two idols. 
14184: 
14185: I can only assume that in his wisdom, he anticipated the rumours that would spread after our victory over Her- nando. Like Solon, he knew that people, hearing of the idol inside the temple, would seek it out. 
14186: 
14187: I imagine that he placed the fake idol at some location nearer to the entrance of the temple, so that if someone did open it up in search of the idol they would come upon the wrong idol first. 
14188: 
14189: But I speculate. I do not know for sure. 
14190: 
14191: I never saw him again. 
14192: 
14193: 
14194: 
14195: For my own part, I could no longer endure living in the horror that was New Spain. I decided to return to Europe. 
14196: 
14197: And so after bidding farewell to the beautiful Lena and the noble Bassario, with the help of several Incan guides I embarked upon a trek through the mountains of New Spain, heading north. 
14198: 
14199: I walked and walked, tlxrough jungles, mountains and deserts until finally I came to the land of the Aztecas, the land that Cortez had conquered in the name of Spain but a few years previously. 
14200: 
14201: There I managed to bribe my way aboard a merchant ship, laden with stolen gold, bound for Europe. 
14202: 
14203: I arrived in Barcelona some months later and from there I travelled to this monastery high in the Pyrenees, a place far away from the world of the King and his bloodthirsty conquistadors, and it was here that I grew old, dreaming every night of my adventures in New Spain and wishing every moment that I could have spent just one more day with my good friend Renco. 
