14530: 
14531: 'But… ?” 
14532: 
14533: 'But I don't believe him.' 
14534: 
14535: 'You don't believe him? Why not?' 
14536: 
14537: 'Does your NRI machine still work?' Race asked Lauren. 
14538: 
14539: 'Yes.' 
14540: 
14541: 'Set it up and I'll show you what I mean.' 
14542: 
14543: 
14544: 
14545: They all moved to the open-topped roof of the citadel, where Lauren began setting up the nucleotide resonance imager. 
14546: 
14547: While she went about setting up the machine, Race looked out over the village. It was dark, still raining lightly. 
14548: 
14549: He caught a glimpse of a large feline shadow peering up at him from behind one of the smaller buildings of the town. 
14550: 
14551: After a few moments, Lauren had the NRI machine ready. She flicked a switch and the silver rod mounted on top of the console began to rotate slowly. 
14552: 
14553: Thirty seconds later, there came a shrill beep! and the rod stopped abruptly. It was not, however, pointing at the idol in Nash's hands. Rather, it was pointing away from Nash, up at the mountains. 
14554: 
14555: 'I'm getting a reading,' Lauren said. 'Strong signal, very high frequency resonance.' 
14556: 
14557: 'What're the co-ordinates?' Race said. 
14558: 
14559: 'Bearing 270 degrees. Vertical angle 29 degrees, 58 minutes. 
14560: 
14561: Range 793 metres. Same as it was last time, if I remember it right,' she said, giving Race a look. 
14562: 
14563: 'You are remembering it right,' he said. 'You'll also 
14564: 
14565: remember that we thought it was inside the temple.' 
14566: 
14567: 'Yes…' Lauren said. 
14568: 
14569: Race looked at her hard—harder than usual. He won dered if she had been party to Nash's deception, decided 
14570: 
14571: 
14572: 
14573: that she probably was. 'Do you remember why we thought it was in the temple?' 
14574: 
14575: Lauren frowned. “Well, I remember we climbed up the crater and saw the temple. Then we figured that the tem ple's location matched the trajectory of the NRI. Ergo, the idol was in the temple.' 
14576: 
14577: 'That's right,' Race said. 'That's exactly what we did. And that's exactly where we went wrong.' 
14578: 
14579: 
14580: 
14581: They all came back inside the citadel. 
14582: 
14583: Race grabbed a pen and a piece of paper from inside the ATV that was still parked flush against the doorway to the citadel. 
14584: 
14585: 'Copeland,' he said to the tall humourless scientist. 'Do you think that with all this technological gadgetry you've got here, you could find me a regular calculator?' 
14586: 
14587: Copeland found one inside one of the American contain ers, handed it to him. 
14588: 
14589: 'All right,' Race said, allowing the others to crowd around him and watch. 
14590: 
14591: He drew a picture on the sheet of paper. 
14592: 
14593: 
14594: 
14595: 'Okay,' he said. 'This is a picture of Vilcafor and the 
14596: 
14597: plateau to the west of it as seen from the side. Okay?' 
14598: 
14599: 'Okay,' Lauren said. 
14600: 
14601: Race drew some lines across the drawing: 
14602: 
14603: 
14604: 
14605: 'And this is what we deduced yesterday from the reading that we got from the nucleotide resonance imager: 793 metres to the idol. Angle of inclination 29 degrees, 58 min- utes-but I'll just use 30 degrees to keep it simple. The point is, when we climbed up the crater and saw the temple, we immediately thought that the temple must have matched the reading. Right?' 
14606: 
14607: 'Right…' Nash said. 
14608: 
14609: 'Well we were wrong to do that,' Race said. 'Do you remember when we were climbing up that spiralling path around the rock tower and Lauren took a reading from her digital compass?' 
14610: 
14611: “Vaguely,' Nash said. 
14612: 
14613: 'Well, I remember it. When we were level with the rock tower, standing on the outer ledge of the rope bridge, Lauren said that we had come exactly 632 metres horizontally from the village.' 
14614: 
14615: He added another line to the drawing and changed the words '793 m” along the hypotenuse—the longest side of the triangle—to 'x m'. 
14616: 
14617: 
14618: 
14619: 632m 
14620: 
14621: 'Anybody remember doing trigonometry at school?' he asked. All the theoretical physicists in the citadel around 
14622: 
14623: 
14624: 
14625: him shrugged bashfully. 'Granted, it isn't nuclear physics,' 
14626: 
14627: Race said, 'but it does still have some uses.' 
14628: 
14629: 'Oh, I see it…' Doogie said suddenly from the back of the small crowd gathered around Race. Clearly the others didn't. 
14630: 
14631: Race said, 'Using simple trigonometry, if you know one angle of a right-angled triangle and the length of one of its sides, you will be able to determine the lengths of the other two sides by using the concepts of sines, cosines and tangents. 
14632: 
14633: 'Don't you guys remember 'SOHCAHTOA'? The sine of an angle equals the length of the side opposite the angle divided by the length of the hypotenuse. The cosine equals the length of the side adjacent to the angle divided by the hypotenuse. 
14634: 
14635: 'In our example here, to find x—the distance between us and the temple—we would use the cosine of 30o.' Race then wrote: 
14636: 
14637: cos30o = 632 
14638: 
14639: x 
14640: 
14641: 'Therefore,' he said, 
14642: 
14643: 632 
14644: 
14645: X . 
14646: 
14647: cos30° 
14648: 
14649: He punched some numbers into the calculator Copeland “ had given him. 
14650: 
14651: 'Now, according to this calculator, the cosine of 30° is 0.866. 
14652: 
14653: Therefore, x equals 632 divided by 0.866. And that is… 729.' 
14654: 
14655: Race amended his drawing accordingly, writing fever ishly. Lauren watched him in astonishment. Ren6e just watched him, beaming. 
14656: 
14657: 
14658: 
14659: 632m 
14660: 
14661: 'Anybody see a problem here?' Race said. 
14662: 
14663: Everyone was silent. 
14664: 
14665: Race amended his drawing one last time, finishing with a flourishing 'X'. 
14666: 
14667: 
14668: 
14669: 632m 
14670: 
14671: 'We made a mistake,” he said. 'We assumed that because of its height the temple was 793 metres from the village and hence, that the idol was inside it. It was a good guess but it was a wrong guess. The real idol isn't inside the temple at 
14672: 
14673: all. It's beyond it, up on the plateau somewhere.“ 
14674: 
14675: 'But where?' Nash said. 
14676: 
14677: 'I would imagine,' Race replied, 'that the idol is to be found in the village of the tribe of natives who built the rope bridge up on the rock tower, the same tribe of natives that attacked our German friends here when they we about to open the temple.' 
14678: 
14679: 
14680: 
14681: 'But what about the manuscript?' Nash said. 'I thought that it said both idols were inside the temple.' 
14682: 
14683: 'The manuscript doesn't tell the full story,' Race said. 'I can only guess that Alberto Santiago doctored the ending so that no-one reading it later would know the true resting place of the idol.' 
14684: 
14685: Race held up the sheet of paper with his drawing on it. 
14686: 
14687: 'That's where the idol is. Your NRI says so, so does the math.' 
14688: 
14689: Nash pursed his lips, thinking. Then at last he said, 'All right. Let's go get it.' 
14690: 
14691: 
14692: 
14693: The two monkeys that Race and the others had caught down by the river had gladly—or perhaps angrily—obliged them with an ample supply of urine, urine which the two screaming primates had sprayed throughout the plastic bags that Race had lined their boxes with. 
14694: 
14695: Put simply, the monkey urine reeked. Its sharp foul odour—the smell of ammonia—pervaded the interior of the citadel. It was no wonder the rapas despised it, Race thought as he and the others applied the warm stinking urine to their bodies. 
14696: 
14697: When they were all done, Van Lewen handed out weapons. Since he and Doogie were the only Green Berets left—so far as anyone knew, Buzz Cochrane was still up on the tower top—they took the two G-11s. Nash, Race and Ren6e were given M-16s, complete with grappling hooks. 
14698: 
14699: 
14700: 
14701: Race, still dressed in his black Nazi breastplate and his blue baseball cap, hung his grappling hook from his belt. 
14702: 
14703: Copeland and Lauren were each given SIG-Sauer P228 semiautomatic pistols. Krauss and Lauren, the ordinary scientists, went gunless. 
14704: 
14705: Once everyone was ready, Van Lewen stepped through the doorway of the citadel and into the ATV. Then he made his way to the rear of the all-terrain vehicle and opened the pop-up hatch. 
14706: 
14707: 
14708: 
14709: His G-11 emerged first. 
14710: 
14711: Then slowly, Van Lewen peered out from the open hatch and scanned the area. Immediately, his eyes went wide. 
14712: 
14713: The big eight-wheeled vehicle was surrounded by rapas. 
14714: 
14715: Their tails coiled and uncoiled behind their massive bodies. 
14716: 
14717: Their yellow eyes bored into him, hard and cold. 
14718: 
14719: Van Lewen counted twelve of them, just standing there in the street, watching him. 
14720: 
14721: Then all of a sudden, the nearest cat snorted—smelled the urine—and immediately reeled away from the ATV. 
14722: 
14723: One after the other, the other cats did the same, turning away from the armoured vehicle and forming a wide circle around it. 
14724: 
14725: Van Lewen stepped out onto the street, his gun up. One by one, the others came out behind him, Race among them. 
14726: 
14727: Like everyone else, he moved slowly, cautiously, staring at the cats while he kept his finger poised on the trigger of his M16. 
14728: 
14729: It was a truly bizarre sensation, a kind of stand-off. Men armed with guns, the cats armed with sheer natural aggression. 
14730: 
14731: Despite their rifles and their pistols, Race was certain that the rapas could take them all down easily if they dared to fire a shot. 
14732: 
14733: But the cats did not attack. 
14734: 
14735: It was as if the humans were protected from them by some kind of invisible wall—a wall which the rapas simply refused 
14736: 
14737: 
14738: 
14739: to cross. Rather, they just followed Race and the others at a safe distance, paralleling them as they made their way toward the riverside path. 
14740: 
14741: Christ, they're huge[ Race thought, as he made his way through the ranks of massive black cats. 
14742: 
14743: The last time he had seen them up close he had been on the other side of the Humvee's glass windows, but now— now that they were all around him, with no windows or doors separating them from him—they looked twice as big. 
14744: 
14745: He could hear their breathing. It was just as Alberto Santiago had described it—a deep-chested braying sound like that of a horse. The sound of a powerful beast. 
14746: 
14747: 'Why don't we just shoot them?' Copeland whispered. 
14748: 
14749: 'I wouldn't go doing that too quickly,' Van Lewen replied. 'At the moment, I think their dislike of monkey urine overrides their desire to kill us. If we open fire on them, I think it's likely that their desire to survive will override their dislike of monkey urine.' 
14750: 
14751: The eight of them made their way up the riverside path and into the narrow fissure in the plateau, the rapas following them at a distance. 
14752: 
14753: They emerged from the passageway at the bottom of the crater and saw the shallow lake stretching away from them, with the rock tower soaring into the sky from its centre and the thin but incredibly tall waterfall pouring down from the south-west corner of the canyon. 
14754: 
14755: For once it wasn't raining, and the full moon shone down on the crater with all its strength, bathing it in a kind of mystical blue light. 
14756: 
14757: Led by Van Lewen, they climbed the spiralling path, up into the night. 
14758: 
14759: The rapas slunk their way up the spiralling path behind them. With their dark black heads and high pointed ears, they looked like demons climbing up out of Hell itself, ready to yank Race and his companions down into the depths of the earth should any of them make one false step. 
14760: 
14761: But ultimately they just kept their distance, put off by the smell of the monkey urine. 
14762: 
14763: 
14764: 
14765: At last the group came to the two buttresses that had once held up the rope bridge. 
14766: 
14767: The rope bridge itself now lay flat against the wall of the tower on the other side of the ravine, exactly where the Nazis had left it. 
14768: 
14769: Race looked across at the tower top. There was no sign of Buzz Cochrane anywhere. 
14770: 
14771: Then, however, instead of crossing over onto the rock towerqwhich, at present, they couldn't do anyway—Van Lewen led them further up the spiralling path, toward the rim of the crater. 
14772: 
14773: The path slid around and behind the thin waterfall at the south-western corner before it rose dramatically, arriving at the rim of the crater. 
14774: 
14775: Race stepped up onto the rim and looked westward— and saw the majestic peaks of the Andes towering above him, dark triangular shadows superimposed on the night sky. Off to his left, he saw the small river that fed the thin waterfall and alongside it, a section of dense rainforest. 
14776: 
14777: A narrow muddy path—created by constant use rather than any deliberate design—ran away from him into the thick green foliage. 
14778: 
14779: But it was what sat on either side of the slender path that seized his immediate attention—a pair of wooden stakes, driven into the mud. 
14780: 
14781: Impaled on each stake was a fearsome-looking skull. 
14782: 
14783: Race felt a chill as he shone his barrel-mounted flashlight onto one of the skulls. 
14784: 
14785: It looked utterly horrific—an effect magnified by the copious amounts of fresh blood and rotting flesh that dangled from its sides. It was oddly shaped too—definitely not human. Rather, both skulls were strangely elongated, with sharp canine teeth, inverted triangular nostrils and wide eye sockets. 
14786: 
14787: Race swallowed hard. 
14788: 
14789: They were feline skulls. 
14790: 
14791: They were rapa skulls. 
14792: 
14793: 
14794: 
14795: “A primitive “Keep Out” sign,' Krauss said, looking at the 
14796: 
14797: two filthy skulls impaled on the stakes. 
14798: 
14799: 'I don't think they're meant to keep people out,' Gaby Lopez 
14800: 
14801: said, sniffing one of the skulls. 'They've been drenched in monkey urine. They're designed to keep the cats away.' 
14802: 
14803: Van Lewen stepped past the skulls and pressed on into 
14804: 
14805: the dense foliage. Race and the others followed him, guided 
14806: 
14807: by the beams of their flashlights. 
14808: 
14809: About thirty yards beyond the two skulls, Van Lewen 
14810: 
14811: and Race came to a wide moat not unlike the one that sur rounded Vilcafor. 
14812: 
14813: The only differences between the two moats were, firstly, 
14814: 
14815: that this moat wasn't dried up—rather, it was filled with .water, the surface of which lay about fifteen feet below the rim of the moat. And secondly, it was inhabited by a family of very large caimans. 
14816: 
14817: 'Great,' Race said as he watched the giant crocodilians 
14818: 
14819: prowling around the bottom of the moat. 'Caimans again.' 
14820: 
