14826: 
14827: Beyond the moat—-completely surrounded by it—Race 
14828: 
14829: saw another section of low foliage, beyond which lay a small collection of thatch huts nestled underneath a stand of tall trees. 
14830: 
14831: 
14832: 
14833: It was a village of some sort. 
14834: 
14835: The short stretch of foliage lay between the village and 
14836: 
14837: the moat, gave the cluster of primitive huts a quaint, almost mystical look. Some torches burned on high sticks, bathing the little town in a haunting orange glow. Apart from the burning torches, however, the village appeared to be completely deserted. 
14838: 
14839: A twig snapped. 
14840: 
14841: Race spun, and immediately saw the pack of rapas standing on the muddy pathway about ten yards behind his group. Somehow, they had managed to get past the urine- soaked skulls and now they were standing a short distance behind Race and the others—watching, waiting. 
14842: 
14843: A narrow log-bridge lay flat on the ground on the village 
14844: 
14845: side of the moat. A length of rope was attached to one end of it in a manner not unlike that which had applied to the rope bridge down at the rock tower. It stretched out over the moat to Race's side, where it was tied to a stake in the ground. 
14846: 
14847: Van Lewen and Doogie pulled on the rope, manoeuvred 
14848: 
14849: the log-bridge into position so that it now spanned the moat. 
14850: 
14851: The eight of them then crossed the bridge and entered the 
14852: 
14853: section of low foliage surrounding the village. 
14854: 
14855: Once they were all over the bridge, Van Lewen and Doogie quickly pulled it back onto the village side of the moat, 
14856: 
14857: so that the rapas could not follow them oven 
14858: 
14859: They all came out from the foliage together, emerging 
14860: 
14861: onto a wide, town square-like clearing. They cast the beams of their flashlights over the thatch huts and tall trees that surrounded the bare dirt clearing. 
14862: 
14863: At the northern end of the square stood a bamboo cage, 
14864: 
14865: its four corners comprised of four thick tree trunks. Beyond the cage—carved out of the muddy wall of the moat—was a large pit about thirty feet square and fifteen feet deep. A criss-crossing bamboo gate separated the pit from the moat itself. 
14866: 
14867: In the very centre of the town square, however, stood the 
14868: 
14869: most arresting sight of all. 
14870: 
14871: It was a shrine of some sort, a large wooden altar-like 
14872: 
14873: 
14874: 
14875: structure that had been carved out of the trunk of the widest tree in the village. 
14876: 
14877: It was filled with nooks and small alcoves. Inside the alcoves Race saw a collection of relics that was nothing short of spectacular—a golden crown embedded with sapphires, silver and gold statues of Incan warriors and maidens, var ious stone idols, and one gigantic ruby that was easily the size of a man's fist. 
14878: 
14879: Even in the semi-darkness, the shrine shone, its treasures glistening in the moonlight. Dense clusters of leaves hung down from the trees around it, framing it on either side like curtains in a theatre. 
14880: 
14881: In the very centre of the wooden shrine—right where its heart would have been—sat the most elaborate nook of all. 
14882: 
14883: It was covered by a small curtain and was quite obviously the centrepiece of the whole altar. But whatever occupied it lay hidden from view. 
14884: 
14885: Nash strode directly over to it. Race knew what he was thinking. With a sharp yank, Nash pulled the curtain cover ing the nook aside. 
14886: 
14887: And he saw it. Race saw it too, and gasped. 
14888: 
14889: It was the idol. 
14890: 
14891: The real idol. 
14892: 
14893: The Spirit of the People. 
14894: 
14895: The sight of it took Race's breath away. Strangely, the first thing that struck him about the idol was what an excellent job Bassario had done in replicating it—his fake idol had been a perfect reproduction. But no matter how hard he had tried, Bassario had been unable to reproduce the aura that surrounded the real idol. 
14896: 
14897: It was majesty personified. 
14898: 
14899: The ferocity of the rapa's head inspired terror. The glint of the purple-and-black thyrium stone inspired wonder. The whole shining idol just inspired awe. 
14900: 
14901: Entranced, Nash reached out to pick it up—at exactly the same moment as a sharpened stone arrowhead appeared next to his head. 
14902: 
14903: The arrow was held by a very angry-looking native who 
14904: 
14905: 
14906: 
14907: had stepped out from the curtain-like foliage to the right of the shrine. He held the arrow poised in his longbow, its drawstring stretched taut back to his ear. 
14908: 
14909: Van Lewen made to raise his G-11, just as the forest all around him came alive and out of it stepped no fewer than fifty natives. 
14910: 
14911: Nearly all of them brandished bows and arrows, all of them aimed squarely at Race and the others. 
14912: 
14913: 
14914: 
14915: Van Lewen still had his gun up. Doogie didn't. He just stood rooted to the spot a few yards away, frozen. 
14916: 
14917: An uneasy stand-off materialised. Van Lewen—armed with a gun that could kill twenty men in an instant—facing off against the fifty-plus natives armed with bows and arrows that were all ready to be fired. 
14918: 
14919: There are too many of them, Race thought. Even if Van Lewen did manage to get a few shots off, it wouldn't be enough. The natives would still kill them all, so over whelming were their numbers. 
14920: 
14921: 'Van Lewen,' Race said. “Don't…' 
14922: 
14923: 'Sergeant Van Lewen,' Nash said from over by the altar, where he stood with an arrow poised next to his head. 
14924: 
14925: 'Lower your weapon.” 
14926: 
14927: Van Lewen did so. As soon as he did, the natives immedi ately moved forward, seized the Americans' high-powered weapons. 
14928: 
14929: An older-looking man with a long grey beard and wrinkled olive skin stepped forward. He didn't bother carrying a long bow. He appeared to be the chieftain of this tribe. 
14930: 
14931: Another man walked at the chieftain's side and as soon as he saw him, Race blinked in disbelief. 
14932: 
14933: This second man wasn't a native at all, but rather was a stout-looking Latin-American man. He was deeply tanned and dressed in the manner of the Indians, but even the lib eral doses of ceremonial paint that he wore on his face and chest couldn't hide his decidedly urban features. 
14934: 
14935: 
14936: 
14937: As the chieftain glared at Nash—standing in front of the shrine like a thief caught with his hands in the till—he growled something in his native tongue. 
14938: 
14939: The Latin-American man at his side listened attentively 
14940: 
14941: and then offered some advice in reply. 
14942: 
14943: 'Hmph,' the chieftain grunted. 
14944: 
14945: Race stood next to Ren6e, the two of them surrounded by five arrow-bearing Indians. 
14946: 
14947: Just then one of the Indians stepped forward—curious— and touched Race on the cheek, as if testing to see if his white skin was real. 
14948: 
14949: Race pulled his face away, jerking it clear. 
14950: 
14951: As he did so, however, the Indian shrieked in astonish ment, causing everyone to turn. He hurried over to the chieftain, shouting, 'Rumaya! Rumaya!' 
14952: 
14953: The chieftain immediately came over to where Race stood, with his white adviser behind him. The old chieftain stood before Race, appraising him coldly while at the same time the Indian who had touched Race's face pointed at his left eye and said, 'Rumaya. Rumaya.' 
14954: 
14955: Abruptly, the chieftain grabbed Race's chin and turned it hard to the right. 
14956: 
14957: Race didn't resist. 
14958: 
14959: The chieftain evaluated his face in silence, inspecting the triangular brown birthmark situated underneath his left eye. 
14960: 
14961: Then the chieftain licked his finger and began rubbing the 
14962: 
14963: birthmark, as if testing to see if it would come off. It didn't. 
14964: 
14965: 'Rumaya…' he breathed. 
14966: 
14967: He turned to his Latin-American adviser and said some thing in Quechuan. The adviser whispered something in return, keeping his voice low and respectful, to which the old chieftain shook his head and pointed emphatically at the square-shaped pit that had been carved into the wall of the moat. 
14968: 
14969: Then the chieftain turned on his heel and barked an order to his people. 
14970: 
14971: The Indians quickly herded everyone except Race into the bamboo cage between the trees. 
14972: 
14973: 
14974: 
14975: For his part, Race was shoved toward the muddy pit adjacent to the moat. 
14976: 
14977: The Latin-American adviser fell into step beside him. 
14978: 
14979: 'Hello,' the man said in heavily-accented English, taking Race completely by surprise. 
14980: 
14981: 'Hey there,' Race said. 'You, ah, want to tell me what's going on here?' 
14982: 
14983: 'These people are the direct descendants of a remote Incan tribe. They observed that you are possessed of the Mark of the Sun—that birthmark under your left eye. They think you might be the second coming of their saviour, a man they know 
14984: 
14985: as the Chosen One. But they want to test you first to be sure.' 
14986: 
14987: 'And how exactly are they going to test me?' 
14988: 
14989: 'They will put you in the pit and then they will open the gate that separates it from the moat, allowing one of the caimans to enter the pit with you. Then they will see who survives the subsequent confrontation, you or the caiman. 
14990: 
14991: You see, according to their prophecy—' 
14992: 
14993: 'I know,' Race said. 'I've read it. According to the prophecy the Chosen One will bear the Mark of the Sun, 
14994: 
14995: and be able to fight with great lizards and save their spirit.' 
14996: 
14997: The man looked at Race askance. 'You're an anthropologist?' 
14998: 
14999: 'A linguist. I've read the Santiago Manuscript.' 
15000: 
15001: The man frowned. 'You've come here looking for the Spirit of the People?' 
15002: 
15003: 'Not me. Them,' Race said, nodding over at Nash and the 
15004: 
15005: others as they were placed inside the bamboo cage. 
15006: 
15007: 'But why? It's worthless in monetary terms—' 
15008: 
15009: 'It was carved out of a meteorite,' Race said. 'And now it's been discovered that that meteorite was made of a very 
15010: 
15011: special kind of stone.' 
15012: 
15013: 'Oh,' the man said. 
15014: 
15015: 'So who are you?' Race asked. 
15016: 
15017: 'Oh, yes, I'm very sorry, I completely forgot to introduce myself,' the man said, straightening. 'My name is Doctor Miguel Moros Marquez. I am an anthropologist from the Uni versity of Peru and I've been living with this tribe for the last nine years.' 
15018: 
