18504: 
18505: Race turned to the first page, started reading. 
18506: 
18507: FIFTH READING 
18508: 
18509: 
18510: 
18511: To the worthy adventurer who finds this notebook. 
18512: 
18513: I write to you now by the light of a torch in the foothills of the glorious mountains that dominate New Spain. 
18514: 
18515: By my amateur reckoning, it is now approximately the Year of Our Lord 1560, nearly twenty-five years after I first came to these foreign shores. 
18516: 
18517: To many who might read this work, it will mean nothing to you, for I write it in anticipation of penning another, fuller account of the remarkable adventures that befell me in New Spain—an account that I may not even write at all. 
18518: 
18519: But if I do write it, and if you, oh, brave adventurer— having come across this notebook through the ministrations of some most noble natives—have indeed read that account, then what follows will certainly have meaning for you. 
18520: 
18521: 
18522: 
18523: It is close on twenty-five years since my incredible adventure with Renco, and all of my friends are dead. 
18524: 
18525: Bassario, Lena, even Renco himself. 
18526: 
18527: But fear not, dear reader, they did not die of any foul deeds or subterfuge. They died in their sleep, all of them, 
18528: 
18529: victims to that villain no man can escape—old age. 
18530: 
18531: Now, I am the last one left alive. 
18532: 
18533: Sadly, as such, I have nothing left to live for in these mountains and so I have decided to return to Europe. I intend to end my days in some distant monastery far away from the world, where God willing, I shall write my amazing tale in full. 
18534: 
18535: 
18536: 
18537: I leave this notebook, however, in the good hands of my 
18538: 
18539: Incan friends—to pass on to their children and their chil dren's children—and to give it only to the most worthy of adventurers, indeed, only those of a stature commensurate with my good friend Renco. 
18540: 
18541: That said, owing to the pedigree of those who will read 
18542: 
18543: this account, I shall endeavour in this notebook to dispel some of the fictions that I intend to include in the larger recounting of my tale. 
18544: 
18545: After the death of Hernando on the enormous stone 
18546: 
18547: tower, Renco did indeed enter the temple with the two idols, but he would emerge soon after, from an underwater passage at the base of the giant finger of stone, safe and sound. 
18548: 
18549: The inhabitants of Vilcafor would abandon their village at 
18550: 
18551: the base of the plateau and relocate to higher ground, to a new 
18552: 
18553: site above the enormous crater that housed the temple. 
18554: 
18555: I would live with them for the next twenty-five years, 
18556: 
18557: enjoying the company of my friend Renco. Why even that rogue Bassario, who proved his worth in our final con frontation with Hernando and his men, became a faithful companion of mine. 
18558: 
18559: But, oh, how I enjoyed my time with Renco. Never have I 
18560: 
18561: had such a good and loyal friend. I feel fortunate to have 
18562: 
18563: bee.n able to spend the greater part of my life in his company. 
18564: 
18565: Oh, and another small tale for you, noble reader—but 
18566: 
18567: one which I beg of you not to tell my holy brethren. 
18568: 
18569: After a time, I would marry. 
18570: 
18571: And to whom, you might ask? Why, none other than the 
18572: 
18573: beautiful Lena. 
18574: 
18575: Yes, I know! 
18576: 
18577: While I had admired her from the first moment I laid 
18578: 
18579: eyes on her, I was not to know that she entertained similar feelings toward me. She thought I was a brave and noble man and, well, who was I disabuse her of that impression? 
18580: 
18581: With her young son Mani—whom Renco doted upon in 
18582: 
18583: the manner of uncles the world over—we made for a won° 
18584: 
18585: derful family, and indeed, soon Lena and I would expand 
18586: 
18587: 
18588: 
18589: a.s. 
18590: 
18591: 
18592: 
18593: our brood to include two delightful daughters who, I say 
18594: 
18595: with pride, were the spitting image of their mother. 
18596: 
18597: Lena and I would be married for twenty-four years, the 
18598: 
18599: most wonderful twenty-four years of my life. It ended but a few weeks ago, when she fell asleep by my side, never to wake. 
18600: 
18601: I miss her every day. 
18602: 
18603: 
18604: 
18605: Now, as the guides prepare to take me north through the forests to the land of the Aztecas, I think of my adventures, and of Lena, and of Renco. 
18606: 
18607: I think of the prophecy that brought us together and I wonder if indeed, I am one of the people mentioned in it. 
18608: 
18609: 
18610: 
18611: There will come a time when he will come, 
18612: 
18613: A man, a hero, beholden of the Mark of the Sun. 
18614: 
18615: He will have the courage to do battle with great lizards, 
18616: 
18617: He will have the jinga, 
18618: 
18619: He will enjoy the aid of bravehearted men, 
18620: 
18621: Men who would give of their lives, in honour of his noble cause, 
18622: 
18623: And he will fall from the sky in order to save our spirit. 
18624: 
18625: He is the Chosen One. 
18626: 
18627: 
18628: 
18629: I ask myself, am I a 'bravehearted man'? 
18630: 
18631: It is strange most strangewbut now, after all that I have been through, I actually think that I am. 
18632: 
18633: 
18634: 
18635: Worthy adventurer, this tale is at an end. 
18636: 
